<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mice with Extra Gene Get Smarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- In an achievement that one day
may be applied to enhance human intelligence, U.S. researchers
have genetically modified mice to be better at learning and
remembering.
</P>
<P>
The researchers, from Princeton University, Massachusetts
Institute of Technology and Washington University, found that
adding a single NR2B gene to mice significantly boosted their
ability to solve maze tasks, learn from objects and sounds in
their environment and to retain that knowledge.
</P>
<P>
Their research, published Thursday in the science journal
Nature and hailed as a "breakthrough" in memory study, revealed a
common biochemical mechanism at the root of nearly all learning.
</P>
<P>
It proved that the NR2B gene is a key switch that controls the
brain's ability to associate one event with another, the core
feature of learning.
</P>
<P>
The NR2B gene is the blueprint for a protein that spans the
surface of neurons and serves as a docking point, or receptor, for
certain chemical signals.
</P>
<P>
After giving mice extra copies of the NR2B gene, and
engineering the genes so that their activity increases as the mice
age, the researchers found that mice with the extra gene had a
much greater learning response than normal mice in a variety of
tests.
</P>
<P>
And, this genetically-modified strain of mice, called Doogie,
also retained into adulthood certain brain features of juvenile
mice, which, like young humans, are widely believed to be better
than adults at grasping large.
</P>
<P>
The finding showed that "genetic improvement of intelligence
and memory in mammals is now feasible, thus offering a striking
example of how genetic technology may affect mankind and society
in the next century", the researchers said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Humans also have the corresponding NR2B gene, although it is
not yet known whether it has the same function in people.
</P>
<P>
However, the scientists believed that in the long-term, the
results may promote further discussions on ethical and social
issues regarding whether and how genetic technology should be used
to modify or enhance mental and cognitive attributes in people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
