<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Praises Signing of Congo Ceasefire Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano has described the signing of the ceasefire in the
Democratic Republic of the Congo as the opening of a new page in
the region's efforts for peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
In his capacity as Chairman of the Southern African Development
 Community (SADC), Chissano said that the signing of the peace
accord by the two factions of the Congolese Rally for Democracy
(RCD) in Lusaka on Tuesday "represents the end of hostilities and
the beginning of a long process for the restoration of peace in
the Congo and in the Great Lakes region".
</P>
<P>
Other parties involved in the Congolese conflict, namely
Angola, Namibia, Uganda, Rwanda, Zimbabwe and the Congolese
government itself, had signed this peace accord on July 10, but
the two RCD groups did not do so then because of their internal
leadership dispute.
</P>
<P>
In a note from the SADC presidency, Chissano expressed the wish
to see the document implemented as urgently as possible, the
process of sending international observers to the Congo,
particularly from the United Nations, "so as to ensure the
implementation of the accord and promote a climate of trust
between the parties involved".
</P>
<P>
The note also congratulated Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
for his commitment in the quest for a lasting peace in the Congo.
</P>
</TEXT>
