<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy to Link Sicily and Mainland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A governmental decree published
Thursday could help pave the way for a link between Sicily and
mainland of Italy, Italian Public Works Minister Enrico Micheli
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"It is a turning point," Micheli said after the government
announced the appointment of advisers who are to assess various
projects to link the Italian largest island of Sicily and the
south region of Calabria in Italian peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"In order to take a decision you must examine costs, the impact
on the environment, time and the effectiveness of the project,"
he said, adding that "only then can you pick out the best
solution."
</P>
<P>
"Sicily urgently needs a link to the mainland, especially now
that there is a united Europe and the single currency, which raise
new challenges for the island's economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian government's decree, the advisers will
have six months to assess technical, financial and environmental
aspects of the projects to link Sicily and mainland.
</P>
<P>
The main contender, according to the decree, is a 3.3km
suspended bridge which the Stretto di Messina company estimated in
1997 would cost 7 trillion lire ( about 3.78 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Another solution, preferred by environmental groups, is for a
"water highway," Micheli says, which would enable high-speed
ferries to cross the straits of Messina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
