<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Israeli, Palestinian Deal Eludes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 2 (Xinhua) -- In a setback in the Middle
East peace, Israel and the Palestinians failed to sign an
agreement over the implementation of the U.S.-brokered Wye peace
deal in Egypt Thursday afternoon as widely expected.
</P>
<P>
Egypt had arranged a signing ceremony in the port city of
Alexandria in the presence of visiting United States Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright. But the Israeli and Palestinian sides
remained deadlocked over the issue of Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted "a senior source" in Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's office as saying that a signing ceremony would apparently
be held in Alexandria Friday morning. A spokesman for the prime
minister said, however, Barak "would not fly anywhere at this
moment."
</P>
<P>
The last obstacle to an agreement on the implementation of the
Wye interim deal, signed and then frozen by Israel's former
hard-line prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu last year, was the
release of Palestinian prisoners jailed in Israel.
</P>
<P>
After the gaps narrowed in rounds of talks lasting for over one
month, the Palestinians demand that Israel release 400 political
prisoners, those jailed for anti-Israel activities. But Israel
insists that it will release only 350 and reiterated it will not
free those who had killed Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators have actually reached the
verge of an agreement after intensive talks since late July. They
have made significant progress on most issues concerning the
implementation of the Wye accord, including a timetable of further
Israeli troop withdrawals from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Wye agreement calls on Israel to hand over 13 percent of
the West Bank to the Palestinians in three stages over a period of
12 weeks. Netanyahu froze the deal after carrying out its first
stage.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have accepted Barak's proposal to divide the
two remaining phases of Israeli troop withdrawals into three
stages and put off the final stage until early next year.
</P>
<P>
Israel has said that if the two sides could not agree on all
issues, it would carry out the Wye agreement as written, meaning
all understandings recently reached including those on the seaport
and safe passages would not be implemented.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the two sides might still have chances to
resolve their difference during Albright's five-day stay in the
region.
</P>
<P>
During a joint news conference with Albright in Alexandria
after the planned ceremony time, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said contacts were going on between Israel and the
Palestinians. He said the U.S. and Egypt were also involved in
the contacts.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who started the visit in Morocco Wednesday, will
arrive in Israel late Thursday night and will hold talks with
Barak Friday. Besides the Palestinian track, she will also
discuss with Barak the resumption of the Israeli-Syrian talks,
which froze three years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Says U.N. Seizing its Kosovo Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 2 (Xinhua) - Yugoslavia Thursday
complained to the United Nations that the U.N. Interim
Administration Mission in Kosovo (UNMIK) illegally seized
Yugoslavia's "public and State property" in the Serbian province
and demanded its return.
</P>
<P>
The complaint came in a letter from Vladislav Jovanovic, charge
d'affaires of the Yugoslav Mission to the United Nations, to the
president of the U.N. Security Council circulated on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Seizing automobiles, funds and buildings, UNMIK is in breach
of its function and in violation of general and international
law," he said.
</P>
<P>
The senior Yugoslav diplomat said this was also a violation of
a Security Council resolution adopted on June 10 setting out
UNMIK's mandate, rights and obligations.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. mission, which operates parallel to a NATO-led
military force called KFOR, is administering Kosovo, the mainly
ethnic Albanian province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
"The attitude of UNMIK constitutes an illegal, arbitrary and
unacceptable usurpation of other persons' assets and a violation
of the basic norms of the status of state property and its
inviolability," Jovanovic said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Yugoslav government "demands the restitution of the
illegally seized property and its return to the legal owner" and
called on the Security Council to instruct UNMIK "not to abuse its
functions in the future and to abide by its mandate" under the
June 10 council resolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Backs Efforts for Lifting of Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) on Thursday
reiterated support for the efforts to have economic sanctions on
Iraq lifted.
</P>
<P>
The nine-year-old crippling international trade embargo on Iraq
should be lifted to ease the sufferings of the Iraqi people, AL
Assistant Secretary General Ahmad Bin Heli said.
</P>
<P>
The 22-nation pan-Arab forum rejects the continued attacks on
Iraqi sites by warplanes of the United States and Britain, Heli
told reporters after a meeting with Iraqi Permanent Delegate to
the Arab League Al-Sultan Al-Shawi.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council imposed the economic
sanctions on Iraq in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait, which
sparked the Gulf War in 1991 to drive Iraqi troops out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British warplanes patrolling the no-fly zones in north
and south Iraq, set up by the West allies after the Gulf War, have
been attacking Iraqi military and civilian targets since December,
causing serious casualties and damage of properties.
</P>
<P>
Heli delivered to Al-Shawi a letter for Iraqi Foreign Minister
Mohammad Said al-Sahaf from the league chief, Esmat Abdel-Meguid,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The letter is a supplement to an earlier message aimed at
clearing the atmosphere for achieving a success for the upcoming
Arab foreign ministers' meeting, the league official said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf will chair the foreign ministers' meeting slated in
Cairo for September 12-13 under rotational system.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Al-Shawi said he briefed Heli on the daily
military aggressions on Iraq by the U.S. and British forces, which
he said jeopardize the unity of Iraq and the security of the
region.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi envoy called upon Arab countries to support Iraq in
standing up to the embargo and aggressions.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shawi hailed the Arab League's rejection of the U.S.-British
air strikes against Iraq and urged Arabs to take a decisive stand
to end the assault. 
</P>
</TEXT>
