<HEADLINE> Namibian Forces Kill 3 Rebels in Caprivi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Namibian security forces
killed three secessionists in a shoot-out early Thursday after
uncovering a " terrorist hideout" in the northeastern Caprivi
Strip, according to report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a ministry statement as saying that security
forces " killed three terrorists" during an operation at the
village of Sibbinda.
</P>
<P>
"The security forces uncovered a secret terrorist hideout in
the Sibbinda area where 10 terrorists were hiding, and this led to
an exchange of fire resulting in three Caprivi Liberation Army
terrorists being killed and two captured," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Sibbinda is about 60 kilometers west of Katima Mulilo, the main
town of the Caprivi region.
</P>
<P>
The statement said: "Among the dead terrorists is Alex Chainda,
a former member of the Namibian Defense Force. War materials were
also captured, among which were seven assault rifles and one
shotgun."
</P>
<P>
Security operations were continuing in the area, it said.
</P>
<P>
The statement warned the rebels to hand themselves over to the
authorities or "be prepared to face extinction."
</P>
<P>
At least 14 people were killed when secessionists attacked
Katima Mulilo on August 2.
</P>
<P>
The secessionists, members of the shadowy Caprivi Liberation
Army, are seeking independence for the Caprivi Strip, a narrow
finger of Namibian territory bordered by Angola, Botswana, Zambia
and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
