<HEADLINE> Int'l Community Urged to Support Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President F. Chiluba
has appealed to international community to cancel the external
debts hanging over the heads of poor countries which were
crippling and destroying hopes of African countries.
</P>
<P>
The president said this when he was meeting with a visiting
British parliamentary delegation in the State House on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said the worry and request to international community was
for assistance with the debts in order to use the money to service
the people.
</P>
<P>
"We are asking for help from the international community in
order to enable us to use the money in which we must service our
education, health and other sectors," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba further said financial assistance was required for
capacity building to enhance democracy in areas like
anti-corruption commission and permanent human rights commission.
</P>
<P>
He also said the country was looking at the area of conflict as
it was impossible to attract investment where conflicts were the
order of the day.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba regretted that peace had not been achieved in Angola
despite spending 14 months discussing the issue in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
He said the recent signing of the peace agreement on the
conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo was for the purpose
of giving the region peace and what system of government the
people wanted.
</P>
<P>
The president also said: "we must make our own efforts to build
and strengthen the economic institutional base in Southern
Africa."
</P>
<P>
That is the case for Southern Africa Development Community
(SADC) and Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA),
also looking at the conflicts issue, "we are making efforts to
stop the conflicts in the Southern African region," the president
said.
</P>
<P>
At the same meeting, Lord Evens, leader of the delegation,
thanked the president for the effort he has made to bring the two
Congolese rebel groups to sign the cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
He also hopes the international conference on HIV/AIDS
scheduled for September 12-16 in Lusaka will find some cure to the
disease on the African continent. 
</P>
