<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Hopeful Palestinians, Israel to Reach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said on Thursday that she is hopeful that the
Palestinians and Israel will soon reach an agreement on the
implementation of the Wye peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Albright made the remarks at a joint press conference with
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa after her meeting with
President Hosni Mubarak in Egypt's Mediterranean port city of
Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
But she said in the meantime that she could only do so much to
bring together the Palestinian and Israeli negotiators, who refuse
to budge in a dispute over the number of Palestinian prisoners to
be freed by Israel under the Wye accord signed last October.
</P>
<P>
"While the United States and Egypt can be helpful, it is up to
the parties themselves to make the hard decisions," she said.
"The negotiations are still going on. We expect them to continue
and we hope very much that they will come to a conclusion as soon
as possible."
</P>
<P>
On his part, Moussa called on the United States to play its
role as the major mediator in the peace talks to help the
Palestinians and Israel reach a resolution.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt does not think that the U.S. will stay on the sidelines
as the peace process is passing through this crucial stage,"
Moussa stressed.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimism that an agreement between the
Palestinians and Israel could be signed in Egypt "within hours, or
within days."
</P>
<P>
Egypt had hoped to host a afternoon signing ceremony of the
Palestinian-Israeli agreement in Alexandria, but night fell with
no agreement.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived in Alexandria from Morocco earlier in the day
on the second leg of her Mideast tour, which will also take her to
Israel, the Palestinian self-rule areas, Syria and Jordan. Her
regional tour is also aimed at seeking ways of helping resume the
Syrian-Israeli negotiations, suspended in early 1996.
</P>
<P>
Although the U.S. administration has billed her tour as a
stock-taking trip, Albright might have to intervene to help the
Palestinians and Israel to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel have agreed on every other
essential issues, including the timetables for the further Israeli
troop pullback from the West Bank and the final status talks under
a revised Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
But the two sides are stuck over the release of a few dozen
Palestinians held in Israeli jails for anti-Israeli activities.
Israel has offered to free 356 Palestinian prisoners while the
Palestinians sought the release of 400. 
</P>
</TEXT>
