<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Zimbabwe Join Hands for Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Zimbabwe
Thursday agreed to expand economic cooperation with a view to
development in the whole region.
</P>
<P>
Projects the two countries were pursuing together would be
speeded up within the context of balanced regional development,
South African President Thabo Mbeki told reporters after meeting
his Zimbabwean counterpart Robert Mugabe in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said: "We are looking at projects where joint efforts
could be made and where we could be much more productive and
progressive than we would be working separately."
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said his meeting with Mugabe focused on matters such as
the development of a gas field in Zimbabwe, and generating
economic activity along the existing road link between Harare and
Beira, Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The Beira corridor would also be discussed with Mozambique with
a view to a tri-lateral effort to maximize the economic potential
of this link.
</P>
<P>
A continuous railway link between Harare and Zambia was another
project under discussion, Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
He said countries in the region would also examine the tourism
potential of cross-border national parks.
</P>
<P>
"The relevant ministers will be dealing with those issues. Task
teams will work on the detail and we will meet again in three
months' time to review progress," Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, together with Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin and
 Agriculture Minister Thoko Didiza, will be in Mozambique Thursday
afternoon for talks with the Mozambican authorities, the Foreign
Ministry said in a statement earlier Thursday. 
</P>
