<HEADLINE> Nepal Boasts of World's Highest Animal Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Nepal is one of the
countries in the world which have the highest animal population
and its unique Himalayan ecosystem and biological diversity
including the genetic pool of domestic animals are resources for
the whole world, said Nepali Minister for Agriculture Chakra
Bastola here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
While inaugurating the 6th International Conference on
Biotechnology in Animal Production, Bastola said that Nepal has 24
indigenous breeds of cattle, buffalo, goat, sheep, pig, horse,
poultry and duck.
</P>
<P>
Available statistics show that Nepal is home to 7.3 million
cows and oxen, 3.3 million buffaloes, 5.7 million goats, 70,000
pigs, about 14.5 million chickens and other pet birds, 50,000 yaks
and 20,000 horses.
</P>
<P>
Bastola asked the participants to find better ways to
effectively utilize Nepal's genetic diversity for both poverty
alleviation and food security in the future, adding that
biotechnology will be the main tool for the enhancement of
productivity of these animals.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Science and Technology Surendra Prasad
Chaudhari said at the conference that Nepal accords high priority
to all scientific and technological endeavors that could enhance
its agricultural production and productivity, as agriculture is
the mainstay of Nepalese economy.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 scientists, professors and cattle farmers from
Japan, the United States , Canada, Indonesia, Egypt, China, India
and Nepal are attending the three day conference starting
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
