<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Urged To Reduce Domestic Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Thursday urged
the Zimbabwean government to mobilize concessional aid from donors
and privatization proceeds to reduce its crippling domestic debt
and to direct more budget expenditure toward poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
World Bank resident representative Thomas Allen made the call
in Harare at the opening of a two-day Structural Adjustment
Participatory Review public forum to assess the impact of
structural and sectoral adjustment and stabilization policies and
to recommend changes in these policies.
</P>
<P>
Allen said that the high level of budgetary interest payments,
accounting for more than a quarter of all budgetary expenditures,
constrained expenditures in support of crucial social services and
poverty reduction activities.
</P>
<P>
"Reducing the stock of domestic debt of the government in order
to cut budgetary interest payments so as to make more money
available for increasing high priority social expenditures has to
be at the core of the strategy," said the World Bank official.
</P>
<P>
This could create a cycle of exchange rate stabilization, lower
interest rates, lower inflation and lower fiscal deficits over the
medium term, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said inflation was the greatest tax on the poor and bringing
it under control through fiscal and monetary stabilization
measures was crucial.
</P>
<P>
The acceleration of the privatization program was not only
important for the reduction of domestic debt, he said, adding
there was evidence that the services provided by these enterprises
could be more efficiently provided by the private sector.
</P>
<P>
A workable land reform program could contribute significantly
to poverty reduction, Allen said, but he lamented that progress in
land reform had been slow and had been clouded by politics.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank official expressed hope that more donors would
extend financial support to Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
