<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibia Probes Links Between UNITA, Secessionists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Namibian authorities
are investigating links between secessionist rebels who attacked a
town in the remote Caprivi Strip a month ago and Angola's UNITA
rebels, Agence France Presse (AFP) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Seven members of the National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA) were deported in mid-August after being arrested
in the Caprivi Strip in a crackdown following the August 2 rebel
attack on Katima Mulilo, AFP quoted Namibian Defense Force Chief
of Staff Martin Shalli as saying.
</P>
<P>
"They were UNITA people, there is no question about it. They
said it themselves," Shalli said.
</P>
<P>
However, it was unclear how they were linked to the attack, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We do not know what they were doing," Shalli said, adding that
they could have been trading with the secessionists, who are
seeking independence for Caprivi, a strip of land sandwiched by
Angola, Botswana, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
He said defense authorities were investigating whether the
seven were in Namibia as individuals or on behalf of UNITA.
</P>
<P>
He said the secessionist rebels got some weapons and equipment
from UNITA people.
</P>
<P>
"we are not sure whether it was (officially) from the movement
or from UNITA bandits selling weapons. But they do have a
connection," Shalli said.
</P>
<P>
One possibility was that UNITA had exchanged weapons for fuel
from the Namibian rebels.
</P>
<P>
At least 14 people were killed in Katima Mulilo, about 1,200
kilometers northeast of the capital Windhoek, in fighting between
the secessionists and security forces.
</P>
<P>
The state of emergency imposed in the region was lifted last
week. "The area is under control," Shalli said.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted The Namibian newspaper as reporting on Thursday that
85 people in connection with the rebel attack were charged with
high treason. 
</P>
</TEXT>
