<HEADLINE> Zhan Xugang Ready for Another Olympic with World Record by sportswriter Zhou Xin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's strongman Zhao Xugang set a new world record at the
current Asian Weightlifting Championships on Thursday to regain
the confidence for his second Olympic gold medal in next year's
Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
"I did not expect to break the world record tonight because I
was in low ebb for almost three years since the Atlanta Olympics,"
said the 25-year-old Zhan after receiving a standing ovation from
the local crowd.
</P>
<P>
Zhan successfully jerked 206.0 kilograms for a new world mark
at his third attempt, surpassing the previous record 205.5kg set
by Aranda Idalberto of Cuba at the Pan America Games in Winnipeg,
Canada last month.
</P>
<P>
"The new world record inspire me for another Olympic gold,"
Zhan said.
</P>
<P>
Zhan, from Zhejian Province, who swept three world records for
his Olympic title in the 70kg in Atlanta, had to change his
division into 77kg as the International Weightlifting Federation
introduced new categories in January last year.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic champion had built his supremacy in the 77kg and
terrorized his Asian rivals as he won all the three titles at the
Asian Weightlifting Championships and Bangkok Asian Games last
year.
</P>
<P>
"Though I broke three Asian records at Bangkok Asian Games, I
still felt lack for confidence to the new division in front of the
elite weightlifters from European countries," Zhan said.
</P>
<P>
"But now I am confident to beat them at any international
competitions," he added.
</P>
<P>
Yang Hanxiong, head coach of the Chinese national team, said:"
We were 60 percent for sure that Zhan would break the jerk world
record, and volatile as he did it."
</P>
<P>
"His victory looms the hope of taking one or two gold medals
for Chinese men's weightlifters at the Sydney Olympic Games next
year," Yang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
