<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Virus Found in Arctic Ice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The discovery of the first
virus preserved in the Arctic ice has prompted a warning that warm
weather may release them into the atmosphere to start new
epidemics.
</P>
<P>
The virus, a common plant pathogen known as tomato mosaic
tobamovirus (ToMV), was found deep within the Greenland icepack by
a team of U.S. researchers, Britain's New Scientist magazine
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The discovery suggested that other viruses, such as ancient
strains of flu, polio and smallpox, may also be entombed and could
make a comeback, the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
"We don't know the survival rate, or how often they get back
into the environment. But it certainly is possible." Tom Starmer,
one of the researchers from Syracuse University, United States,
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Starmer and his colleagues had earlier found ToMV in clouds and
fog. The researchers thought they might find the virus in the ice
because it is widespread, moves in the atmosphere, and is very
stable.
</P>
<P>
So they examined four ice cores, from three sites in Greenland,
containing ice between 500 and 140,000 years old.
</P>
<P>
As they had suspected, the researchers detected RNA from the
tomato pathogen. Further sequencing revealed that 15 strains of
the virus were present.
</P>
<P>
The frozen viruses were probably still infectious because of
strong protein coats which allow them to survive in harsh
environments, the scientists said, warning that they may be
released to cause outbreak of disease as the ice is melting
constantly around the poles.
</P>
<P>
The researchers are planning to use other techniques to find
out if virues are still viable in other cores taken from Antarctic
and Arctic ice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
