<HEADLINE> Security Council Hails Rebels' Signing of Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Thursday voiced its welcome to rebels' signing of a
ceasefire accord on the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press, the president of the Security
Council for the month of September, Arnold Peter van Walsum, said,
"Council members welcomed the signing of the Lusaka ceasefire
agreement" on the Democratic Republic of Congo by the Congolese
Rally for Democracy (RCD), which took place on August 31 in
Lusaka, capital of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after the 15-nation Security Council met in
a closed-door session to hear a briefing on the situation in Congo
(K) by Kieran Prendergast, U.N. under-secretary-general for
political affairs, and Hedi Annabi, assistant secretary-general
for peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
"Council members urged all parties to abide strictly to the
ceasefire agreement and to refrain from any action putting it at
risk, so that peace can become a reality in the DRC," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Council members reiterated their continuing support for the
involvement of the United Nations in the peace process, in which
the U.N. will cooperate closely with the Organization of African
Unity," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Council members welcomed the imminent deployment of the first
group of military liaison officers in accordance with relevant
Security Council resolution, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council "commended the efforts by all African
leaders, particularly by the president of the Republic of Zambia,
Frederic Chiluba, to try to resolve the conflict in the DRC
peacefully," the statement said.  
</P>
