<HEADLINE> Trimble Pessimistic Over N.Irish Peace Pact Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Protestant Ulster Unionists
leader David Trimble warned Thursday that Northern Ireland's peace
process review does not stand much chance of success.
</P>
<P>
Trimble said a major review of the pact, due to start Monday,
faced stalemate because the Irish Republican Army's political
wing, Sinn Fein, had not "declare themselves for the democratic
way."
</P>
<P>
"In some ways, the Sinn Fein leadership are going backwards,"
Trimble said in an interview with the London-based New Statesman
magazine.
</P>
<P>
"I can't see the prospect in the next month or two, which means
that I can't, as things stand at the moment, see any prospect of
the (Mitchell) review succeeding."
</P>
<P>
U.S. mediator George Mitchell, who chaired talks that produced
the Good Friday peace accord, will lead the review hoping to end a
logjam over IRA disarmament and creation of a coalition provincial
government.
</P>
<P>
Trimble again criticized a controversial British ruling that
the IRA's ceasefire remains intact, and he warned the IRA may be
gearing up for murder.
</P>
<P>
He said British intelligence agencies had been told that the
IRA "had a shortage of high quality handguns needed for
close-quarter killings. The (IRA's) Belfast Brigade in particular
needed these weapons. This is the word that's coming through....
They're for close-quarter killing."
</P>
<P>
Trimble's party, the pro-British Ulster Unionist Party, and
Sinn Fein are expected to delay until Saturday decisions on
whether they will participate in the review. 
</P>
</TEXT>
