<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Stress at Office Causes "Desk Rage" in UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Growing pressures of the
workplace and long working hours are creating a growing phenomenon
of "desk rage" in British offices, said a survey published
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
As stress builds to intolerable levels, workers are
increasingly venting their frustration on colleagues, the study by
Britain's ICM Research has found.
</P>
<P>
More than a quarter of employees questioned by the ICM study
admitted that they had been upset by rows with colleagues.
</P>
<P>
And a third said that other people's rudeness was a major
source of stress at work, while a fifth blamed "problems with work
colleagues" for making their lives miserable.
</P>
<P>
Nearly two-thirds of the 674 adults surveyed said they were
affected by workplace stress, with more than half (56 percent)
saying that it had caused them to lose sleep.
</P>
<P>
ICM's latest study echoed the conclusion of another survey
conducted last month, which found that workplace stress in Britain
is worse that anywhere else in Europe or North America.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the findings, Sue Keane, of the British
Psychological Society, said that the extent to which disputes with
colleagues or clients were adding to the widely recognized
pressures caused by heavy workloads and tight deadlines.
</P>
<P>
"We have road rage, now we are seeing `desk rage' as conflicts
boil over between colleagues," she said.
</P>
<P>
Keane advised that "just a few minutes out of the office or
workplace at lunchtime could make all the difference." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
