<HEADLINE> European Markets Slide Amid Steep Wall St. Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets slid on
Thursday as robust U.S. economic data rekindled interest rate
fears.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 was confined to the red for all but the
opening moments of trading, with concerns over U.S. interest rates
paramount.
</P>
<P>
The index ended down 80.6 points to 6195.6, as many traders
kept a wide berth of markets ahead of U.S. unemployment figures
due out on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Telecom, bank and utility stocks absorbed some of the biggest
shocks. Bank of Scotland plunged 5.68 percent to 728 pence as rate
fears rattled the sensitive financial sector.
</P>
<P>
HSBC Holdings lost 2.67 percent after it said its merger with
Republic New York may take longer to complete because of a probe
into a Republic unit. Lloyds slipped 2.55 percent, Barclays gave
back 2.78 percent, and Abbey National skid 2.12 percent.
</P>
<P>
Legal &AMP; General shares rose sharply on the session, sparked by
speculation that it is about to be the subject of a takeover bid.
</P>
<P>
The life assurance group's 10 percent rise came against a
background of a limp UK stock market, depressed by weakness among
the telecom and banking shares.
</P>
<P>
German Dax closed more than 2 percent weaker at 5189.92 points,
weighed down by weaker U.S. shares.
</P>
<P>
Paris stocks closed down, dragged lower by the poor performance
of both U.S. and European markets. The Cac 40 closed down 1.8
percent or 82.78 points at 4550.60.  
</P>
