<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake of 4.7 degrees
on the Richter scale jolted Chile's 4th Region some 500 kilometers
north of the capital city of Santiago Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter was 27 kilometers west of Punitaqui, said the
Seismology Institute of the University of Chile.
</P>
<P>
No damage has been reported so far.
</P>
<P>
The same day, a 4.5 degree earthquake hit the southeastern
Mexican State of Chiapas, but caused no personal or material
damage.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter was situated along the Pasific coast of Chaiapas
State, 20 kilometers beneath the surface of the Earth.
</P>
<P>
A report from the Seismology Institute said the earthquake was
caused by movements of the tectonic plate. 
