<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Fall On Fear Of Higher Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks fell
Thursday as fears of higher interest rates spread the market.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 94.67 at
10,843.21. The blue chip index fell as much as 205 points during
the trading.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index fell 11.96 at 1,319.11 and the technology heavy Nasdaq
composite index fell 16.56 at 2,734.24.
</P>
<P>
Fears about higher interest rates sparked after the Labor
Department reported that the growth of American workers'
productivity slowed considerably in the second quarter while labor
costs jumped sharply.
</P>
<P>
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan has said that if new
data suggest that the pace of labor cost and price increases will
be picking up, the Federal Reserve will have to act promptly and
forcefully to keep inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
Those fears escalated as Federal Reserve Governor Edward Kelley
told Market News International Thursday that it would be premature
to assume the Federal Reserve will wait until next year to raise
rates again. The Federal Reserve raised rates twice in the past
two months in a bid to preempt inflation from the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
A dismal earnings outlook from Sears and other retailers also
helped to push stocks lower.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 5.96 at 611.33 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 3.98 at 779.21. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 3.57 at 427.42.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 12-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 2,082 dow, 867 up and 577
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 684.35 million shares from 697.14
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
