<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's "Power Tiger" Bows to Market Law (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Ertan Hydro-Power Station
in southwest Chin's Guizhou Province went on line in August last
year and this was hailed as the largest of its kind built in China
this century.
</P>
<P>
Since then, however, general manager Liu Junfeng of the station
has become increasingly anxious as it has been very difficult to
sell his product.
</P>
<P>
With four of the six generators installed and operating so far,
Ertan is capable of generating 10 billion kwh of electricity a
year, but to date Liu has only signed 6.4 billion kwh in contracts.
</P>
<P>
"That means a loss of at least one billion yuan for this year,"
he said. In the coming years, it will be an even tougher job for
Liu's salesmen when the station installs the last two generators
which will add seven billion kwh more to Ertan's power output.
</P>
<P>
China's power industry, which has been under the State monopoly
for decades, used to be nicknamed "Power Tiger" by the people
because it could act as it pleased, regardless of requirements or
complaints from customers.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese remember the days when the "Tiger" was dominant.
Unexpected and frequent stoppages of the power supply often caused
a large amount of waste for factories and damaged electric
appliances in homes.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, as many large power plants have come on line,
formerly strutting power producers have had to face an
increasingly competitive market.
</P>
<P>
The current economic restructuring, especially in the State
sector, has allowed local companies to enjoy greater autonomy over
their internal affairs, including the right to choose their own
power suppliers, by a consideration of price and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, differing economic strengths among localities are
another factor.
</P>
<P>
In the developed coastal province of Guangdong in south China,
power stations are working all-out to meet the demands by local
industries that are the main beneficiary of the country's reform
and opening-up drive.
</P>
<P>
But in underdeveloped areas such as Sichuan Province in the
southwest, local hydro-power electric plants may lose as much as
13.8 billion yuan this year, due to the sluggish market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Science-Technology Expo Opens in Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A three-day China science and
technology achievements exposition was launched here Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
The exposition is organized by the Chinese Ministry of Science
and Technology to mark the 50th anniversary of the founding of new
China and Macao's upcoming return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
On display are more than 180 items of scientific and
technological achievements or products covering satellites,
rockets, telecommunications, electronics, machinery, biology,
medicine, health care, chemical industry, architecture and
environment protection.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition is aimed at making local residents know more
about the scientific and technological development in the interior
areas of China in recent years, and it is an opportunity to
publicize scientific knowledge, according to the organizers.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it enables Macao businesspeople to explore
cooperation with the research institutes or companies in the
interior, the organizers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
