<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading Israeli newspapers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli police and its General Security Service have
arrested an Israeli arab on suspicion of murdering a Jewish
couple last week. The suspect told police he had acted alone,
although investigators there was the possibility of further
arrests.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Despite her previously stated intention of not getting
involved, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright spent her
first day of her Middle East tour Thursday in a frantic attempt
to mediate between Israel and the Palestinian National
Authority. If Albright succeeds in bridging the gaps between the
two sides, a deal may be signed at the Erez check point between
Israel and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- The opposition Likud party Thursday held elections for
its leadership. According to an opinion poll among party
members, former Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon would get more
than 50 percent of the vote and be elected as the party
chairman.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- As Israel and the Palestinians are close to sign a
deal over implementing the Wye agreement, Israeli security forces
warned against possible terror attacks in the country. Meanwhile,
the security forces would be reinforced around the country. 
</P>
