<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-National Day special Urbanites In China Living More Comfortable Lives (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Now, the symbol of wealth is the telephone, mobile phone, air-
conditioner, personal computer, and car.
</P>
<P>
By 1998, there were 105 color TVs for every 100 urban families,
91 washing machines, 76 refrigerators, 76 telephones, 20 air-
conditioners, 4 computers and 0.25 cars.
</P>
<P>
Urban housing has improved remarkably over the past two decades.
In 1981, only 14 percent of urban families had more than 8 square
meters of living space for each member. The figure rose to 48
percent in 1988 and to 77 percent in 1998. In 1981, as much as 37
percent of urban families did not have their own house, or had
less than 4 square meters of living space for each member. The
figure now only 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Perhaps the figure that speaks the loudest is that of bank
deposits. In 1952, individual bank deposits amounted to only 900
million yuan. That figure began to increase at an incredible rate
after 1978, when it was 21 billion yuan to 233.8 billion yuan by
1986. By the end of 1998, Chinese banks held 5.34 trillion yuan in
individual deposits, a 254-fold increase from 1978. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
