<HEADLINE> British Tourists Jailed for Possession of Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Five British tourists were
jailed Thursday for one month in Cyprus after pleading guilty to
possessing a small quantity of hard drugs, local mass media
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
They were identified as Natasha Wright and Mark Alexander
Lambie, both 26, Josef Jacobs Green, 43, Errol O'Neil Gordon and
Richard Samuels, 27.
</P>
<P>
Police said they all were from London.
</P>
<P>
"The possession and use of drugs by foreign tourists in Cyprus
has grown to worrying proportions and the imposition of prison
sentences has become inevitable," said Judge Leonidas Kalogirou.
</P>
<P>
The five were arrested in Cyprus' southeast Ayia Napa town on
August 28, following a search of three apartments where they were
staying.
</P>
<P>
The search found five ecstasy pills and a small bag of cannabis.
</P>
<P>
The five admitted to buying the drugs from a dealer in Ayia
Napa.
</P>
<P>
Drug squad officers are trying to track down a narcotics gang
who they believe supply illegal substances to British tourists in
Ayia Napa.
</P>
<P>
Over 1 million British tourists are expected to visit Cyprus
this year, with most flocking to Ayia Napa's club scene. 
</P>
</TEXT>
