<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 07:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amnesty in Danger Due to Gangs: Turkish Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Justice Minister
Hikmet Sami Turk has said the new amnesty bill passed by the
parliament is likely to benefit gangs in the country.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Turkish President Suleyman Demirel rejected the
amnesty law, which had he approved it, would have freed almost
half of the country's convicts.
</P>
<P>
The president's rejection was in response to the public outcry
over the law, which would have put hundreds of killers and mafia
leaders back on the streets once it was legislated.
</P>
<P>
Demirel has sent the bill back to the parliament, asking
legislators to make revisions that take "justice, rules of
equality and public conscience" into account.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Turkish Prime Minister Develet Bahceli has said it is
natural for the president to listen to the public opinion and
veto the amnesty.
</P>
<P>
"But we wish he had to listen to the government as well, " he
said.
</P>
<P>
However, Demirel Thursday approved a bill that offers
conditional pardon for journalists and writers who have been
jailed for expressing their views.
</P>
<P>
Judicial officials said that at least 50 journalists and
writers will benefit from the conditional pardon.
</P>
<P>
The president also approved another law that pardons civil
servants who have violated the discipline codes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
