<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 600 Illegal Aliens Arrested in Kenyan Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Police in Kenya's capital
Nairobi have arrested more than 600 suspected illegal aliens,
recovering two pistols and some assorted pieces of communications
equipment in a night swoop.
</P>
<P>
The operation which began shortly before midnight Wednesday and
went on till Thursday morning was conducted by a 1,000-strong
force, including officers from the paramilitary general service
unit, the regular police and the administration police, local
newspapers reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Nairobi Provincial Police officer Peter Mbuvi said Thursday the
swoop was mainly intended to nab illegal aliens, illegal
possessors of firearms and communications equipment as well as
suspects with stolen goods.
</P>
<P>
Mbuvi noted that the arrested suspects, including Somalis and
Ethiopians, comprised refugees who had sneaked out of the camps,
illegal aliens residing in the country and those possessing either
firearms or other equipment illegally.
</P>
<P>
For the refugees arrested, he stated, they would have to either
be taken back to refugee camps or be repatriated back to their
respective countries. Others will be charged in court and illegal
aliens be deported.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi announced on July 22 this year
the closure of Kenyan-Somali border citing rampant insecurity and
influx of firearms into Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Mbuvi reiterated that the security personnel in the capital
were determined to rid the city of illegally acquired firearms
and to reduce the crime rate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
