<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosperity Returns to Ancient Silk Road (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Parts of the remote ancient
Silk Road are once again echoing to the bustle and buzz of
business as trade and commerce have returned with a vengeance to
Urumqi, one of the gateways linking the East and the West.
</P>
<P>
This week an estimated 10,000 business people from home and
abroad are attending the ongoing Eighth Urumqi Economic and Trade
Fair in this capital of northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The event, one of the six major regional fairs in China, was
established in the wake of a state strategy to make the border
areas of the country prosperous.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 years ago, Xinjiang was a crucial section of the
Silk Road,an economic route linking China with central Asia and
Europe in the Tang Dynasty (618-907). Its importance waned after
sea routes flourished and the environment along the Silk Road
deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, though remaining an underdeveloped area in China,
this remote region is enjoying an increasing popularity among
investors because of its abundant natural resources and
attractive investment conditions.
</P>
<P>
According to Huang Jun, a research fellow at the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences, Xinjiang is rich in land resources,
petroleum and cotton. Both domestic and foreign investors are
confident that Xinjiang is attractive because of its improving
infrastructure and a series of preferential policies from the
local government.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang, the largest region of ethnic groups in China, shares
a border with eight countries. Currently, 15 posts and 60 counties
are open to the outside world, and two economic development zones
and three border cooperation zones authorized by the central
government with greater powers to trade with countries across the
border have been established.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Stock Index Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Xinhua A stock index
dropped 4.70 points to close at 206.07 and the Xinhua B stock
index dipped by 0.64 points to finish at 37.80 today.
</P>
<P>
The Xinhua Stock Index is China's first national unitary stock
exponent, which is jointly designed and issued by the Economic
Information Department of the Xinhua News Agency and Beijing
University.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosperity Returns to Ancient Silk Road (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Xinjiang has now become a huge cotton market as well as an
important center for grain, livestock and sugar, due to the
efforts since the 1990s of revitalizing this western area of the
country," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
A modernized industrial system featuring petrochemicals,
building materials, textiles and the food processing industry is
also taking shape in Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
So far, 32,000 kilometers of highways, 2,000 km of railways and
14 airports have formed a modern transportation system for this
remote region, shortening the distance between Xinjiang and the
rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
The region is also rebuilding the highways around the Tarim and
the Junggar basins following the completion of 44 roads leading to
foreign countries. And the extension project for the South
Xinjiang Railway line going westward to Kashi will be completed at
the end of this year. Consequently, the Tarim Basin will be no
longer isolated, which will facilitate the exploitation of
petroleum and cotton production.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kashi International Airport, which is the most
important aviation port in Northwest China, is being expanded.
</P>
<P>
An advanced telecommunications network will also help Xinjiang
to become more well-known to the outside. Using the longest inland
communication optical fiber cable in the world, the network will
link the cities of Xi'an, Lanzhou, Urumqi and Yili, all in
northwest China, with developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to this improvement in communications, and a better
investment environment, Xinjiang is being transformed into a busy
commercial hub in the western regions of China.
</P>
<P>
The border trade volume alone had rocketed from 320 million US
dollars in 1992 to 870 million US dollars last year, an annual
growth rate of 42 percent. Xinjiang is now the second largest
region in terms of border trade turnover in China.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 400 foreign funded enterprises have been set up in
the region, with actual investment of 2.2 billion US dollars.
Similarly, over 1,000 projects with investment totalling 7.8
billion yuan from other parts of China have been set up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New AIDS Vaccine Trials to Start Next Year in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The first preliminary trials
for a new AIDS vaccine developed by British and Kenyan scientists
are due to start early next year among volunteers in Oxford,
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Following tests on primates, which saw 70 percent of the
animals turning HIV-resistant, scientists believe that a
preliminary stage of trial on humans is now ready to begin,
Friday's Daily Nation newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
It is said that the vaccine is likely to stimulate the key
"killer T- cells" in human body so as to hold the virus at bay.
</P>
<P>
The research team has promised that if the trials are
successful, the AIDS vaccine will be available to Kenyans at
prices which even the poor can afford.
</P>
<P>
However, it is still likely to be some years before the trials
are completed.
</P>
<P>
While there are around 25 kinds of AIDS vaccines being
developed worldwide, the research in Kenya and Britain is one of
the few to involve a combination of DNA research with a more
conventional approach based on the vaccine used to immunize
against smallpox.
</P>
<P>
Last January, Andrew McMichael of Oxford announced that a group
of Nairobi prostitutes had demonstrated HIV-resistance after
using the vaccine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
