<HEADLINE> New Zealand Dollar Slump Drives up Japanese Car prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Buyers of Japanese cars in
New Zealand are facing a five percent to 12 percent increase in
prices after the NZ dollar trade-weighted index has slumped to a
six-year low.
</P>
<P>
At Friday's rate, the price on a small Japanese sedan has
increased to 28,000 NZ dollars (14,560 U.S. dollars) from 25,000
NZ dollars (13,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand dollar trade-weighted index, a measure of the
dollar against the currencies of New Zealand's main trading
partners, dropped to 54.65 Thursday, its lowest since July 1993.
</P>
<P>
The slump was most marked against the Japanese yen where it
fell to 56.77 yen Friday and neared the all-time low of 53.43 yen
touched in April, 1995. 
</P>
