<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Child Labor to End by 2005 in Nepal: Industrialist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Child labor from the carpet
industry, one of the biggest employers of child labor, could be
wiped out by the year 2005, The Kathmandu Post quoted a carpet
industrialist as saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to wipe out child labor from the country
within the next six years," said carpet industrialist Bimal Nepal,
who is also general secretary of the National Society for
Protection of Environment and Children (NASPEC), an organization
working to phase out child labor.
</P>
<P>
Nepal was addressing an interaction program on NASPEC's Role on
Phasing Out Child Labor from the Carpet Industry Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The phasing-out process includes rescuing child workers from
the carpet industry and rehabilitating them with non-formal
education, counseling, health services and vocational training.
Over one thousand child workers have been rescued by the
organization.
</P>
<P>
There are 2.6 million child workers in Nepal which make up
nearly half of the child population in the country. About half of
them have worked without pay.
</P>
<P>
A research conducted by the organization revealed that 46
percent of child workers were aged between 10 and 12, followed by
40 percent aged 13 and 14. Most of these children came from the
central region of Nepal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
