<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of India's Political Events (1): (1947-1979) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are India's
major political events from 1947 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
On August 15, 1947, India became independent from the
Commonwealth. Jawahar Lal Nehru, Congress leader, became India's
first prime minister.
</P>
<P>
On November 26, 1949, the Constituent Assembly approved a
republican Constitution, providing for a president as head of
state.
</P>
<P>
On January 26, 1950, India became a republic, although
remaining a member of the Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
In May 1964, Nehru died and was succeeded by Lal Bahadur
Shastri.
</P>
<P>
In 1965, India and Pakistan fought a second war over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
In January 1966, following mediation by the U.S.S.R, Shastri
and President Ayab Khan of Pakistan signed a joint declaration,
aiming at a peaceful settlement of the Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
In August 1969, the presidential election was held. Two
factions of Congress supported different candidates, and the
success of Indira Gandhi's candidate split the party. The
Organizations Congress, led by Morarji Desai, emerged in November.
</P>
<P>
In March 1971, Indira Gandhi's wing of Congress won 350 of the
515 elective seats in the House of the People (Lok Sabha)
elections.
</P>
<P>
In March 1977, a general election to the House of the People
was held. The election resulted in a victory for the Janata Party,
chaired by Morarji Desai, who became prime minister. The Janata
Party and an allied party, the Congress for Democracy, together
won 298 of the 540 seats. Congress obtained 153 seats.
</P>
<P>
In January 1978, Indira Gandhi became leader of a new breakaway
political group, the Congress Party, known as the Indian National
Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Factsheet (7): Economic Statistics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 3 (Xinhua) --
</P>
<P>
Fiscal year: April 1-March 31 of the next year
</P>
<P>
Gross Domestic Product: 385 billion U.S. dollars (1997)
</P>
