<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Peruvians Remit 1 Billion Dollars Home Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, September 2 (Xinhua)-- Peruvians living abroad remit
around 1 billion U.S. dollars to their families every year,
reports from Lima said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Remittances are fundamental for many families, especially the
middle and lower middle classes. In our investigation we have
found that many families depend exclusively on the remittances",
Professor Teofilo Altamirano of the Ponticia Catholic University
said in a report.
</P>
<P>
Investigators estimated that the sum of money sent back is up
to some 1 billion dollars every year, but it's difficult to know
exactly how much money overseas Peruvians have remit home.
</P>
<P>
Altamirano said that in the case of Western Union, one of the
firms that transfers money, the monthly movement of capital is
around 10 million dollars, with an average of 500 dollars per
remittance, which represented about 10 percent of the total
remittances sent back to Peru.
</P>
<P>
Western Union and its main competitors represented 29 percent
of remittances, while another 25 percent was made through banks
and the remaining sum (around 600 million dollars) was brought
into Peru through informal channels, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
