<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Factsheet (1): General Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 3 (Xinhua) --
</P>
<P>
Official name: The Republic of India
</P>
<P>
Area: 2,974,700 square kilometers
</P>
<P>
Geography: The Republic of India forms a natural subcontinent
with the Himalaya mountain range to the north. It faces the Indian
Ocean to the west (the Arabian Sea) and to the east (the Bay of
Bengal). The countries having a common border with India are
Afghanistan and Pakistan to the northwest, China, Bhutan and Nepal
to the north, Myanmar to the east and Bangladesh to the east of
West Bengal. Sri Lanka is separated from India by a narrow channel
of sea formed by the Pak Straits and the Gulf of Mannar.
</P>
<P>
Population: estimated at 980 million in 1999 (the world's
second largest). Average annual population growth rate is about
2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Capital: New Delhi with a population of around 10 million.
</P>
<P>
Languages: The official languages are Hindi, spoken by about 30
percent of the population, and English. The Indian Constitution
also recognizes 17 regional languages, of which the most widely
spoken are Telugu, Bengali, Marathi, Tamil, Urdu and Gujarati.
</P>
<P>
Religion: About 80 percent of the population are Hindus and 11
percent Muslims. There are also Christians, Sikhs, Buddhists and
others.
</P>
<P>
National Flag: Three horizontal stripes of saffron, white and
green with the wheel of Ashoka in the Center in blue.
</P>
<P>
National Anthem: Jana-gana-mana (Thou art the ruler of the
minds of all people; words by Rabindranath Tagore).
</P>
<P>
Defense Forces: in 1998 the total strength of the India's armed
forces was 1,175,000 -- an army of 980,000, a navy of 55,000 and
air force of 140,000. Defense budget is 412 billion Indian rupees
(10.70 billion U.S. dollars) in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Factsheet (3): Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Constitution of India
provides for a bicameral Parliament consisting of the president
and two Houses known as the Council of States (Rajya Sabha) and
House of the People (Lok Sabha).
</P>
<P>
The Rajya Sabha, at present, has 245 seats, of which 12 are
nominated by the president and others are elected indirectly by
the elected members of the legislative assemblies. It is a
permanent body not subject to dissolution, but one-third of its
members retire every second year by rotation and are replaced by
newly elected members.
</P>
<P>
The Lok Sabha at present consists of 545 members. Of these, 543
members are directly elected while two are nominated by the
president to represent the Anglo-Indian community. The term of the
Lok Sabha, unless dissolved, is five years from the date appointed
for its first meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
