<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Arctic Research Highlights Global Climate Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Because it is an
important influence on the world's climate, the North Pole's
impact on the earth was the focus of the recently concluded
Chinese arctic research expedition, Chen Liqi, chief scientist of
the expedition, said today.
</P>
<P>
Aboard the homeward-bound ship Snow Dragon, Chen pointed out
that the resources and environmental changes of the North Pole may
potentially influence the environment in the future.
</P>
<P>
Chen noted that in the past 50 years, the temperature in some
polar areas rose one to two degrees centigrade, the frozen earth
belt moved northward, and glaciers receded.
</P>
<P>
These phenomena, accompanied by an ever thinner ozone layer,
has intensified the amount of ultraviolet radiation, and obviously
this indicates changes in the global climate.
</P>
<P>
Considering that the interaction between cold airflow from the
Arctic and hot airflow from the tropics deeply affects China's
climate, Chinese scientists are intensely focused on the Arctic
effects, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
"China will benefit from Arctic research," Chen added.
</P>
<P>
During the recent Arctic research, one major subject of concern
was how the eco-system and biologic resources of the Arctic Ocean
will affect the development of the Chinese fishing industry.
</P>
<P>
China has been engaged in Arctic research since the 1980s, and
took part in the International Arctic Science Committee in 1996.
This January, the Chinese State Council approved China's first
Arctic expedition, which came to a successful end last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
