<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Software Piracy Continues to Impair U.S. Communities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A Microsoft-sponsored
study released Thursday showed that software piracy still inflicts
a severe impact on states and local communities across the United
States, despite increased attention to the issue from both
government and industry.
</P>
<P>
The software piracy rates rose last year in the country's 21
states, including California and Virginia, where much of the
recent growth in the technology sector has been fueled.
</P>
<P>
"Although we have made some gains in protecting intellectual
property and reducing the impact of software piracy worldwide,"
Microsoft said in a statement, "criminal counterfeiting and the
Internet has posed distinct challenges for Microsoft and the rest
of the software industry in battling this issue."
</P>
<P>
According to the study, losses for the 10 most affected states
including California, Texas and New York amounted to some 3.5
billion U.S. dollars, or 57 percent of the nation's total.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, communities nationwide lost over 1 billion dollars in
tax revenues, about 40 million dollars above the 1997 level.
</P>
<P>
The study said that 29 states had piracy rates higher than the
national average of 25 percent. And eight states among them had
rates over 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft said that last year it filed actions against 168
resellers for distributing counterfeit software and hard disk
loading -- the practice of installing pirated software in
computers sold to consumers.
</P>
<P>
The company did not say how much it suffered in terms of money,
but confirmed that more than 43 million units of counterfeit
Microsoft software were seized in the country last year.
</P>
<P>
Consumers using counterfeit software could find they are
missing key elements including computer code, have higher risk of
viruses, and are ineligible for technical support or upgrade, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
By pirating software or spending money on counterfeit products,
Microsoft added, consumers also are inadvertently contributing to
causing losses in the form of tax revenue and employment in an
industry that has recently been responsible for much of the growth
of the U.S. economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polar Research to Be Int's Scientific Focus Next Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Scientific research in the
North and South poles will become a hot research topic in the
international scientific community in the new century, said
Chinese scientists who have just completed their 56-day Arctic
expedition, the first of its kind by Chinese scientists.
</P>
<P>
Chen Liqi, the home-bound chief scientist of the Chinese North
Pole expedition, said: "The earth is a whole system, in which the
North and South poles are playing an ever increasing role."
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the peculiar geographic positions and the
unique natural environments of the poles provide ideal locations
to study the evolution of the earth and the global climate changes.
</P>
<P>
"Global changes and human environmental problems have become
not only a research object for scientists, but also a major
concern for more and more political figures. In the next century,
many more governments and scientists will join the cause of polar
study," said the chief scientist.
</P>
<P>
Chen is also in charge of China's polar research activities.
China's first North Pole expedition demonstrated China's concern
about the world's environmental problems, and Chinese scientists'
strong sense of responsibility to make contributions to precisely
forecasting and solving environmental problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
He mentioned in particular that 15 years ago, the late senior
Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping pointed out that the purpose of China
's polar research is "to make due contributions for the peaceful
use of the polar areas."
</P>
<P>
Chen Liqi also said that "the ability to conduct polar
expedition is a clear illustration of a nation's comprehensive
national strength, especially its scientific and technological
establishment. With China's scientific research level elevated to
a new high, we will be more active in polar research, mainly on
environmental issues." 
</P>
</TEXT>
