<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile, Costa Rica Negotiate Trade Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica and Chile on
Thursday started negotiations on a protocol of tariff reductions,
sources from the Costa Rican Foreign Trade Ministry told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries reached 49.1 million U.S.
dollars in 1998. Chile exported 29 million U.S. dollars worth of
products to Costa Rica, which in return exported 20 million
dollars to Chile.
</P>
<P>
Chile, Costa Rica, Nicaragua, Honduras, El Salvador and
Guatemala ended talks on parts of the standards of a free trade
treaty here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Due to their different levels of development, the norms of
access to free trade markets will be negotiated in a bilateral way.
Now Chile and Nicaragua have started talks with their partners and
hoped to conclude them before next month, the same deadline set by
Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
The other three Central American countries have decided to
negotiate together with Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Imports Large Amount of Edible Oil in 1998-99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar imported a total of 112
million U.S. dollars' worth of edible oil in fiscal 1998-99, which
ended in March, according to the latest official figures published
by the country's Central Statistical Organization.
</P>
<P>
Of a total of over 340,000 tons of annual consumption of edible
oil by the Myanmar people, per capita consumption of the oil
reached 7.3 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Although annual domestic production of edible oil is just over
180,000 tons, the country still needs to import nearly 160,000
tons of the oil annually, which accounts for 46.6 percent of the
country's total oil demand.
</P>
<P>
The main reasons for Myanmar's domestic insufficiency of edible
oil are said to be due to less cultivated areas for oil crops,
low annual per-hectare output and fast increase of population.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuadoran Economy Expects Slight Growth in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador's gross domestic product
(GDP) is expected to grow 3 percent in the year 2000 to 15
billion U.S. dollars from the projected 14.4 billion dollars this
year, the government said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the 1999-2000 general budget, the government predicted a 200
million dollars increase in its total revenue from the targeted 2.
7 billion dollars for 1999.
</P>
<P>
Tax incomes is to increase from 1.8 billion dollars in 1999 to
nearly 2 billion dollars next year.
</P>
<P>
The export of crude oil will reap 710.7 million dollars next
year, 224.1 million dollars more than 1999, according to the
forecast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
