<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Praises China's Efforts in Poverty Alleviation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 3 (Xinhua) -- China's achievement in poverty
alleviation has attracted worldwide attention and served as a
model for many countries, a senior official of the World Food
Program (WFP) said in a recent interview here with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past 20 years, the impoverished population in China
has been decreasing by an annual average of 10 million and this is
a great success for China," said Judy Cheng-Hopkins, WFP director
in charge of Asian affairs, who made a working visit to China last
month.
</P>
<P>
She said that in the past 20 years, in contrast to the
worsening situation of poverty in many countries and regions, the
Chinese government allocated huge amounts of funds for poverty
alleviation, and by the end of 1998, the impoverished population
in rural areas dropped to 42 million from 250 million in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Hopkins said she was satisfied with the implementation of the
WFP's 62 development projects and three emergency projects in
China at a value of 876 U.S. million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Hopkins, who has 21 years of experience in the U.N. system,
said that since the mid-1980s, China has implemented integrated
agricultural development projects instead of direct food aid in
the impoverished regions. "These projects are very appreciated by
the WFP."
</P>
<P>
Noting that the government's high political will and right
policy have guaranteed the successful poverty relief work, she
expressed confidence that China will eventually win the battle
against poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Striving to Become Key Int'l City (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's leading
industrial and commercial city, will begin to gain status as a key
international city by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
"By then, Shanghai will basically reach the level of a modern
international metropolis in terms of overall economic strength,
economic structure, city layout, and cultural and educational
progress," said Mayor Xu Kuangdi in an exclusive interview with
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Xu, also an academician with the Chinese Academy of Engineering,
said that by then the city will haven taken major steps toward its
final goal of becoming an international center of economy, finance
and trade.
</P>
<P>
According to Xu, what Shanghai has achieved over the past 50
years has laid a firm foundation for further development.
</P>
<P>
From 1949 when the People's Republic was founded, to the mid-
sixties, Xu said, the city managed to create a complete industrial
system comprising nearly every industry and began playing a major
role in helping the country form an independent industrial system.
</P>
<P>
China's first 10,000-ton ocean-going vessel, first missile,
first satellite, and first jumbo jet were all manufactured in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The central government's 1990 decision to turn the Pudong New
Area in the eastern part of Shanghai into a financial and trade
zone has given great impetus to the local economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Becomes 5th Largest Recipient of Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Mexico has become the
fifth largest recipient country of foreign investment in the world
and the third largest in Latin America over the past five years,
the authorities said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The annual foreign investment inflow to Mexico has increased
from 3 billion U.S. dollars to an average 11 billion dollars since
President Ernesto Zedillo took power in 1994, said Carlos Garcia,
chief of Foreign Investment at the Secretariat of Trade.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's foreign investment totaled 15 billion dollars at the
end of 1994, and amounted to over 60 billion dollars by last June,
Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
The investment increase was attributed mainly to Mexico's entry
into the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) at the end of
1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
