<HEADLINE> Larsen's Poor Performance Disappointing, Danish Manager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Danish team manager Thomas
Lund was disappointed with men's singles second seed Poul-Erik
Hoyer-Larsen's poor performance in the Indonesia Open badminton
tournament.
</P>
<P>
Larsen had to unexpectedly bow out to Malaysian rookie Yap Yong
Jyen 13-15, 12-15 in the third round of the tournament in Bali on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Hoyer-Larsen didn't play really well today (Thursday). He
seemed like he didn't have any confidence. Yap played well and
used many chances. Under normal circumstances, Hoyer-Larsen would
win," Lund was quoted by The Jakarta Post Friday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hoyer-Larsen, the 1996 Olympics gold medalist and world number
four, could not hide his disappointment with his poor result.
</P>
<P>
"I wanted to finish the match immediately but I lost control.
Statistically, I would have won over him in nine of the 10 matches.
I believed I wouldn't lose to him, but I underestimated him. I'm
quite disappointed in the way I was playing. Actually, it was a
very good draw, so I can't complain to anybody," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lund also commented on another Dane player Peter Rasmussen's
performance against Indonesian Hendrawan.
</P>
<P>
Hendrawan, ranked 17th in the world defeated world number seven
and fourth-seeded in the tournament Rasmussen 15-6, 15-10.
</P>
<P>
"He was on the bad side of the court in the first set. I think
he played quite well and tried to use his chances. But Hendrawan
survived some bad points. Hendrawan could control the game and the
win. He also played really good nets, he's a very confident player,
" Lund said.
</P>
<P>
It was the second time Rasmussen lost to the Indonesian players.
In the early rounds, he also bowed out to Marlev Mainaky in the
second round of the Singapore Open last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
