<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Minister Tells French How Much Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A senior government minister of
China told a 700-person French audience Thursday that the changes
the Chinese people have experienced in the past 100 years are the
biggest ever in their 5,000-year history.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Qizheng, director of the Information Office of China's
State Council, made the speech entitled "Chinese People Meet the
21st Century" at the United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization (UNESCO) headquarters here on the first day
of the China Culture Week -- '99 Paris.
</P>
<P>
He said that the purpose of his speech is to let the French
people know better about China's past and present and make a
comparison between the situation of the Chinese people at the
beginning of the 20th century and 100 years afterwards.
</P>
<P>
Zhao said that 100 years ago, China was living under full
humiliations inflicted by foreign invaders and was looked down
upon by other countries.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, a Dutch dictionary published at that time
explained the word "Chinese" as "foolish men and mentally ill
men." Another example, an American newspaper published in the
early 19th century a cartoon which compared a Chinese man with a
swine.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, because of their poor health and archaic habits, the
Chinese people bore the nickname "Sick man of East Asia" until
1949, when the People's Republic of China was founded, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
As for the status of Chinese women at the beginning of the 20th
century, Zhao said that their feet were bound and prevented from
grow since they were little girls, and they were the private
properties of their husbands after marriage.
</P>
<P>
A typical situation of Chinese women at that time was described
by Ba Jin, a famous Chinese writer, in his novel "Family," which
has been translated into French and many other languages, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
