<HEADLINE> Security Council Sanctions Committee Okays Iraqi Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
committee overseeing sanctions against Iraq has approved Baghdad's
donation of 10 million U.S. dollars in oil to assist the victims
of the devastating earthquake that jolted Turkey on August 17,
U.N. officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Council members did not object to Iraq's plan to provide
500,000 barrels of oil to Turkey, according to a spokesman for the
chairman of the committee.
</P>
<P>
The donation will not count against Iraq's export limit as
governed by the United Nations oil-for-food program, which allows
Iraq to use the revenue from oil sales to purchase humanitarian
supplies.
</P>
<P>
Iraq Wednesday announced its donation of 10 million U.S.
dollars in urgent oil assistance to Turkey, which suffered
devastation damage and loss of human lives caused by an earthquake
in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
A news release from the Iraqi Mission to the United Nations
said, "The Iraqi government donated for relief a quantity of Crude
Oil equivalent in value to an amount of 10 million U.S. dollars,
to be distributed by the Turkish Red Crescent Society to the
Turkish families victims of the earthquake in Turkey."
</P>
<P>
"Iraq have started from August 29 to pump through the
Iraqi-Turkish pipeline a quantity of 100,000 barrels of oil a day
for a period of 5 days for a total of about 500,000 barrels," the
news release said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced the donation despite the hardship caused by the
continuation of what Baghdad called "the unjust comprehensive
sanctions imposed by the Security Council."
</P>
<P>
"On the last day, Iraq shall pump an additional quantity to
make up of any shortage to reach an equivalent amount of 10
million U.S. dollars," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"It is worth noting that Iraq has ranked first in providing
humanitarian emergency assistance to Turkey," the news release
said. "The second rank is left to the U.S."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council's sanction committee approved unofficially
Tuesday on Iraq's proposed donation in oil to Turkey's earthquake
victims, diplomats here said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is expected to sell the oil and donate the revenues to
the Turkish Red Crescent Society to aid those made homeless in the
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
The crude oil to be donated to Turkey will flow through the
same pipeline to the Turkish port of Ceyhan that carries about 45
percent of the oil sold under the U.N. oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
The plan, an exception to the sanctions, allows Iraq to sell
5.26 billion U.S. dollars in oil every six months to buy needed
humanitarian supplies for its people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
