<HEADLINE> British Women Soccer Agent Wins over Men's Dinner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- British woman Rachel Anderson,
the world only female agent licensed by soccer's governing body
FIFA, claimed victory in discrimination lawsuit on Thursday after
she was barred from the British player union's all-male awards
dinner.
</P>
<P>
According to the Reuters report, Anderson's case hinged on
whether the Professional Football Association (PFA) annual dinners
in 1997 and 1998 were public or private events. Private functions
are not subject to the Sexual Discrimination Act.
</P>
<P>
"They said it was a private event but it's very hard to argue
that when you've allowed an agency to sell tickets on your behalf
to members of the public," Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
"I was obviously very pleased that I won but disappointed that
it had to go as far as that."
</P>
<P>
Anderson, who represents dozens of British professionals, won 7,
500 pounds (12,000 U.S. dollars) in damages but said that was not
the reason she brought the lawsuit against the PFA.
</P>
<P>
"I think they've realized that they've got to conform to public
opinion and a changing world," she said. "Women are part of
everyone's life whether people like it or not and certainly part
of business life and certainly football now." 
</P>
</TEXT>
