<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hepatitis More Dangerous Than AIDS: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Hepatitis "B" and "C" are
one hundred times more contagious than AIDS and the number of
patients dying from hepatitis "B" in one day is equal to that of
those dying from AIDS in one year, according to experts attending
a discussion program here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The experts concurred that hepatitis "B" will ultimately lead
to liver cancer and takes life within a short period of time after
contracting the disease. They said that the disease claims lives
of some two million people every year around the world and the
people dying from it in Nepal ranges from 500 to 1,000 every year.
</P>
<P>
Hepatitis "B" and "C" are one of the main causes for liver
cirrhosis and cancer. Eighty percent of liver cancer cases are
caused by this disease. More than 80 percent of cases are found in
Africa and Asia.
</P>
<P>
The virus causing the disease is found in blood, semen and
vaginal path.
</P>
<P>
According to Chairman of the Liver Foundation in Nepal Santosh
Shrestha, lactating mothers who are suffering from any infection,
alcoholics and persons who suffer from long fever and diarrhea are
more likely to contract the disease.
</P>
<P>
Persons who establish sexual contact with more than one person
and those who have received blood many times are also likely to
contract the disease.
</P>
<P>
The disease also spreads through handkerchiefs, bed sheets,
toothbrush, shaving blades and scissors used by the patient.
Tattooing, acupuncture, piercing of nose and ears, frequent use of
needles and treatment of teeth may also contribute to the spread
of the disease, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
