<HEADLINE> U.S. Suspects Russian Mafia Has Moles in U.S. Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. authorities suspect
that Russian organized crime groups may have put "moles" inside
the U.S. financial system, The Wall Street Journal reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the authorities as saying that the criminals
set people up with jobs to help them launder money and conduct
other illegal transactions, placing the moles in key positions at
major banks and securities firms.
</P>
<P>
"They'll put people in sensitive positions in the bank so they
can utilize them at some later point," a law-enforcement official
who investigates Russian rings in the U.S. told the journal.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the U.S. authorities based their concerns
on information from informants and other confidential sources but
not on public evidence, which they said is scant.
</P>
<P>
The probe is part of a broader investigation into a number of
alleged money-laundering cases at U.S. banks. The initial
investigation centered on the Bank of New York, but has widened in
recent days.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government has called allegations of Russian
involvement in money laundering a smear by Western media and
denied loans from the International Monetary Fund (IMF) are
diverted illegally. 
</P>
