<HEADLINE> Hurricane Dennis Weakens But Still Menacing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Dennis, which reduced from
a hurricane to a tropical storm Tuesday, continued to lash U.S.
east coastal areas with gusting winds Thursday, spitting rain for
the fourth day in a row and taunting meteorologists who warned
that the storm could still regain strength and become a hurricane
again.
</P>
<P>
The storm remained nearly stalled less than 160 kilometers off
the coast of North Carolina State, astounding weather experts and
confounding residents who had put their lives on hold.
</P>
<P>
Along the coast from North Carolina to Delaware, four straight
days of churning winds kept many beaches closed and carried away
hectares of sand, including the sand that once swelled in front of
the Virginia Beach boardwalk. Crews in Ocean City, Maryland State,
cleared piles of drifted sand from the boardwalk and washing
crusted salt from power lines.
</P>
<P>
In North Carolina, where President Bill Clinton Wednesday
declared nine counties eligible for federal disaster funds because
of Dennis, some 5,000 people, mostly residents, who stayed on
Hatteras Island after Sunday's evacuation order remained stranded
when the only north-south highway became impassable.
</P>
<P>
Dennis had weakened enough by Wednesday morning that officials
at the National Hurricane Center considered stripping it of its
tropical storm status as well. But airborne observations showed
that a storm eye may be reforming on its western side, a sign that
Dennis is likely to remain a serious threat well into the weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Productivity Growth Slows While Labor Costs Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Labor Department said
Thursday that growth of U.S. workers' productivity slowed
considerably in the second quarter while labor costs rose sharply.
</P>
<P>
Productivity, the amount of output for each hour of work,
increased at an annual rate of 0.6 percent in the April-June
quarter, far below the 3.6 percent rate in the first three months
of the year.
</P>
<P>
The unexpected smaller 0.6 percent increase was revised
downward from the Department's initial estimate a month ago that
productivity had risen 1.3 percent in the April-June quarter.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, unit labor costs, a key measure of wage
pressures, jumped at an annual rate of 4.5 percent in the second
quarter, the largest increase since the first quarter of 1994 when
they also rose 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan has told Congress
that recent strong gains in productivity were likely to moderate.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan and many other economists believe the good showing on
productivity has helped keep inflation low.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan has warned that if productivity slows, wage pressures
are likely to quickly surface, given that labor markets are the
tightest in nearly three decades.
</P>
<P>
The 0.6 percent increase in productivity was the slowest
quarterly increase since the second quarter of 1998, when
productivity rose only at a 0.4 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in productivity reflected the fact that the gross
domestic product also slowed sharply to an annual rate of 1.8
percent in the second quarter of this year, compared to 4.3
percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, productivity increased by 2.2 percent, almost double
the 1.2 percent gain of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan has noted this sharp improvement as evidence to
support his view that the nation's heavy investment in computers
and other productivity-enhancing technology is beginning to pay
off.
</P>
<P>
The 4.5 percent rate of increase in unit labor costs compared
to modest increases of just 2 percent in 1998 and 2.3 percent in
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibia Probes Links Between UNITA, Secessionists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Namibian authorities
are investigating links between secessionist rebels who attacked a
town in the remote Caprivi Strip a month ago and Angola's UNITA
rebels, Agence France Presse (AFP) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Seven members of the National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA) were deported in mid-August after being arrested
in the Caprivi Strip in a crackdown following the August 2 rebel
attack on Katima Mulilo, AFP quoted Namibian Defense Force Chief
of Staff Martin Shalli as saying.
</P>
<P>
"They were UNITA people, there is no question about it. They
said it themselves," Shalli said.
</P>
<P>
However, it was unclear how they were linked to the attack, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We do not know what they were doing," Shalli said, adding that
they could have been trading with the secessionists, who are
seeking independence for Caprivi, a strip of land sandwiched by
Angola, Botswana, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
He said defense authorities were investigating whether the
seven were in Namibia as individuals or on behalf of UNITA.
</P>
<P>
He said the secessionist rebels got some weapons and equipment
from UNITA people.
</P>
<P>
"we are not sure whether it was (officially) from the movement
or from UNITA bandits selling weapons. But they do have a
connection," Shalli said.
</P>
<P>
One possibility was that UNITA had exchanged weapons for fuel
from the Namibian rebels.
</P>
<P>
At least 14 people were killed in Katima Mulilo, about 1,200
kilometers northeast of the capital Windhoek, in fighting between
the secessionists and security forces.
</P>
<P>
The state of emergency imposed in the region was lifted last
week. "The area is under control," Shalli said.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted The Namibian newspaper as reporting on Thursday that
85 people in connection with the rebel attack were charged with
high treason. 
</P>
</TEXT>
