<HEADLINE> Britain to Support Turkey's Bid for EU Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain said on Thursday it
would argue for Turkey to be recognised as an European Union (EU)
candidate at a weekend meeting of EU foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
"We will be arguing for that (candidate) status to be
recognised...this weekend among foreign ministers," Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook told reporters after talks in London with his
Turkish counterpart Ismail Cem.
</P>
<P>
Cook said Turkey's application should be judged by the same
standards as any other candidate for EU membership.
</P>
<P>
"That must be on the same tests and no other test as any other
candidate," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Cook said both Britain and Turkey recognised there was "much
work to be done" over Turkey's application.
</P>
<P>
He said Turkey is a country of great strategic importance and
significance to Europe and has been a good friend of Europe.
</P>
<P>
The European Union froze Turkey's long-standing membership bid
two years ago, citing its poor human rights records and political
standards.
</P>
<P>
Cook said Britain would also argue for generous economic
support for Turkey after last month's earthquake killed more than
14,000 people and devastated its industrial north-west region.
</P>
<P>
"Looking beyond the crisis, we recognise that there will be a
requirement for longer term economic reconstruction. I will argue
that the European Union is to recognise the new situation in
Turkey and the need for the EU to respond generously and
appropriately with the economic reconstruction for Turkey," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
