<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African States Urged to Increase Health Budgets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A World Health
Organization (WHO) official Thursday called on African countries
to increase their health budgets to cope with the diseases they
face.
</P>
<P>
WHO regional director Ebrahim Samba said at WHO's annual
meeting in Namibian capital Windhoek that the Namibian government
has allocated about 15 percent of its budget to health and that
the other 45 sub-Saharan countries that make up WHO African region
should follow suit.
</P>
<P>
Health budgets of the countries in the region are between six,
seven and eight percent of their respective budgets, South African
Press Association quoted Samba as saying.
</P>
<P>
Five years ago, the majority of African countries allocated
less than five percent of their budgets to health.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue our advocacy to place health at the center of
 development," he added. "No country can develop when the people
are sick."
</P>
<P>
Sub-Saharan Africa carries among the world's heaviest burdens
of HIV/ AIDS, tuberculosis and malaria.
</P>
<P>
Samba said the numerous conflicts in the region were also
damaging health, noting that the WHO had for years urged its
members to end conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Twenty of the 46 countries in the region are involved in some
sort of war, he said.
</P>
<P>
With about nine million refugees, "Africa (has) the highest in
the world. Internally displaced persons -- 30 million -- the
highest in the world," Samba said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that 70 percent of the total land mines in the
world are in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The damage to infrastructure, hospitals, buildings, the roads
... is just terrible. In some countries, you will see they have
gone back 30 years in their development," Samba said.
</P>
<P>
The five-day conference reviewed the region's work against
HIV/AIDS, making health accessible to all, and prioritizing mental
health.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, 70 percent of new infections of HIV in the world were
recorded in sub-Saharan Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
