<HEADLINE> Marion Jones Won't Compete Again This Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Multi-talented sprinter-
jumper Marion Jones of the United States, who collapsed during the
World Athletics Championship last week due to back injury, still
has back spasms and will not compete again this season, her agent
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"She continues to improve, but she is not well enough to
compete," Charlie Wells said in a telephone interview from
Brussels, Belgium Ones had hoped to compete in a Golden League
meet there Friday.
</P>
<P>
The pulling-out decision would put an end to Jones' hope of
sharing the one million U.S. dollars as bonues offfered to
athletes who compete the Golden League season undefeated in their
specialties. Jones is one of the three runners who had won all
five of their European circuit races previously.
</P>
<P>
Only the final meet in Berlin next week remained in the Golden
League after Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Jones, the unbeatable sprinter in the 100 and 200 meters so
far, collapsed on the track in the semifinals of the women's 200
meters at the world championships in Seville, Spain, suffering
from cramps and back spasms.
</P>
<P>
She returned to the United States over the weekend for further
evaluation. Her doctors recommended she not compete again this
season, Wells said.
</P>
<P>
The world No. 1 sprinter had hoped to win four gold medals at
the world championships. She successfully defended her 100 meter
title but finished third in the long jump.
</P>
<P>
Wells said the injury will not change Jones' determination to
seek an unprecedented five gold medals in the Sydney Olympics next
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
