<HEADLINE> Rwandan Minister Admits Embezzling Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan Minister of Education
Emmanuel Mudidi has admitted that important sums of money were
embezzled in the ministry's project of reconstruction and
rehabilitation of schools in the country.
</P>
<P>
He had been summoned by parliament to explain corruption in an
International Development Association (IDA) 227 Credit worth 26
million U.S. dollars, the Rwanda News Agency (RNA) reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He told lawmakers Wednesday that embezzlement, which hit the
World Bank project which started in 1995 and was due to end by
this September, caused a loss of over 150 million Rwandan franc
(one U.S. dollar equals to 355 Rwandan franc at current exchange
rate).
</P>
<P>
Mudidi acknowledged that up to now, only 23 million dollars
have been used.
</P>
<P>
However, Mudidi said that the case of corruption has been
submitted to courts which are handling it.
</P>
<P>
Some people involved in this scandal have already been arrested
and asked to return the money.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the project was set up to
reconstruct schools during the emergency period after the 1994
genocide.
</P>
<P>
It was planned to rehabilitate over 3,000 school blocks and
replace school equipment and stationary in the schools.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, parliamentarians have decided to
follow up another corruption case in which the government is said
to have lost 350 million Rwandan franc to one Rwandan businessman.
</P>
<P>
Corruption is currently at the top of evils the authorities
have stepped up measures to eradicate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
