<HEADLINE> Albright in Egypt for Talks on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright arrived in Alexandria, Egypt Thursday on the
second leg of her regional tour aimed at helping push the Mideast
peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
Albright went straight into talks with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak after arriving in the Mediterranean port city to seek ways
to bridge the gap between the Palestinians and Israel over an
agreement on the implementation of the Wye peace accord signed
last October.
</P>
<P>
Although the United States administration has billed Albright's
Mideast tour as a stock-taking trip, it appeared that she might
have to help the Palestinians and Israel overcome last-minute
obstacles to the agreement which was supposed to be signed in
Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
A difference over the number of the Palestinian prisoners to be
released by Israel is holding up the Palestinian-Israeli
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Israel has offered to free 356 Palestinians held for
anti-Israeli activities while the Palestinians sought the release
of 400. The two sides refused to budge in the dispute.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel have reached agreement on the
timetables for further Israeli troop pullback from the West Bank
and the final status talks in addition to the opening of two safe
passages between the Gaza Strip and the West Bank for the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Albright began her Mideast tour with a visit to Morocco. After
her trip in Egypt, she will also travel to Israel, the Palestinian
self-rule areas, Syria and Jordan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
