<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Patten Hits Out at N.Irish Police Report Leak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Former Hong Kong governor Chris
Patten on Thursday hit out at the leaking of his report into the
future of Northern Ireland's police force, saying some media
reports were aimed at derailing the province's peace process.
</P>
<P>
"It has been extremely frustrating," Patten told BBC radio.
"There have been some things which I can only imagine are an
attempt to muddy the water before we report."
</P>
<P>
The Belfast Telegraph newspaper said last week that Patten
would recommend the Royal Ulster Constabulary (RUC) be renamed the
"Police Service of Northern Ireland".
</P>
<P>
Political parties, including the Irish Republican Army's
political wing Sinn Fein, might have places on a new police
supervisory board, it said.
</P>
<P>
Policing is one of the province's most divisive issues. More
than 90 percent of RUC officers are Protestant.
</P>
<P>
Protestant politicians have always made clear they would see
any name change for the RUC as an attempt to appease Northern
Ireland's minority Catholic community by removing any reference to
the British crown.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein has branded the force anti-Catholic and wants it
abolished.
</P>
<P>
Patten, who will deliver his report next week as former U.S.
Senator George Mitchell launches a review of the problems holding
up last year's Good Friday peace accord, said the newspaper had
been indulging in "educated guesswork".
</P>
<P>
"I hope that there then can be a full and serious debate on an
issue which is absolutely fundamental to the question of whether
or not Northern Ireland continues to develop as a peaceful,
democratic society," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
