<HEADLINE> Ghaddafi: Libya Welcomes Foreign Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TRIPOLI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Libya welcomes more foreign
investments and the Libyan people are sincere in international
economic cooperation, said Libyan leader Muammar Ghaddafi here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The West always accused Libya of being against international
trade and closing our country by ourselves. This is not true,"
said Ghaddafi at the opening of the two-day Symposium on Prospects
of International Investment and Trade in the Great Jamahiriya.
</P>
<P>
Ghaddafi told the symposium, which drew about 40 businessmen
from 30 countries, that Libya is important for foreign investors
because it is situated at the entrance of Africa and it enjoys a
coastline of 2,000 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Libya intends to be the transit line for trade between northern
and southern Africa, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan leader assured foreign investors that "we have laws
to protect foreign investments and incentives to attract
investments."
</P>
<P>
Libya's General People's Congress (parliament) passed in 1997
Law No. 5 to attact investment of foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
Libya remains subject to tough sanctions from the United
States, who accused Libya of supporting terrorist activities.
Libya's asset in the U.S. are frozen, and Americans are banned
from engaging in trade with Libya or traveling to the country.
</P>
<P>
Libya has claimed that the seven-year United Nations sanctions
against Libya, which had been in place since 1992 after the
Lockerbie bombing, has caused the country to lose 24 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan government has been making efforts to draw
investment to revitalize the country's oil-dependent economy after
the U.N. suspended the sanctions on Libya in April after Libya
handed over the two Libyans suspected of bombing a Pan Am flight
over Lockerbie, Scotland in 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
