<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Says U.N. Seizing its Kosovo Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 2 (Xinhua) - Yugoslavia Thursday
complained to the United Nations that the U.N. Interim
Administration Mission in Kosovo (UNMIK) illegally seized
Yugoslavia's "public and State property" in the Serbian province
and demanded its return.
</P>
<P>
The complaint came in a letter from Vladislav Jovanovic, charge
d'affaires of the Yugoslav Mission to the United Nations, to the
president of the U.N. Security Council circulated on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Seizing automobiles, funds and buildings, UNMIK is in breach
of its function and in violation of general and international
law," he said.
</P>
<P>
The senior Yugoslav diplomat said this was also a violation of
a Security Council resolution adopted on June 10 setting out
UNMIK's mandate, rights and obligations.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. mission, which operates parallel to a NATO-led
military force called KFOR, is administering Kosovo, the mainly
ethnic Albanian province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
"The attitude of UNMIK constitutes an illegal, arbitrary and
unacceptable usurpation of other persons' assets and a violation
of the basic norms of the status of state property and its
inviolability," Jovanovic said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Yugoslav government "demands the restitution of the
illegally seized property and its return to the legal owner" and
called on the Security Council to instruct UNMIK "not to abuse its
functions in the future and to abide by its mandate" under the
June 10 council resolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
