<HEADLINE> AL Backs Efforts for Lifting of Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) on Thursday
reiterated support for the efforts to have economic sanctions on
Iraq lifted.
</P>
<P>
The nine-year-old crippling international trade embargo on Iraq
should be lifted to ease the sufferings of the Iraqi people, AL
Assistant Secretary General Ahmad Bin Heli said.
</P>
<P>
The 22-nation pan-Arab forum rejects the continued attacks on
Iraqi sites by warplanes of the United States and Britain, Heli
told reporters after a meeting with Iraqi Permanent Delegate to
the Arab League Al-Sultan Al-Shawi.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council imposed the economic
sanctions on Iraq in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait, which
sparked the Gulf War in 1991 to drive Iraqi troops out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British warplanes patrolling the no-fly zones in north
and south Iraq, set up by the West allies after the Gulf War, have
been attacking Iraqi military and civilian targets since December,
causing serious casualties and damage of properties.
</P>
<P>
Heli delivered to Al-Shawi a letter for Iraqi Foreign Minister
Mohammad Said al-Sahaf from the league chief, Esmat Abdel-Meguid,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The letter is a supplement to an earlier message aimed at
clearing the atmosphere for achieving a success for the upcoming
Arab foreign ministers' meeting, the league official said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf will chair the foreign ministers' meeting slated in
Cairo for September 12-13 under rotational system.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Al-Shawi said he briefed Heli on the daily
military aggressions on Iraq by the U.S. and British forces, which
he said jeopardize the unity of Iraq and the security of the
region.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi envoy called upon Arab countries to support Iraq in
standing up to the embargo and aggressions.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shawi hailed the Arab League's rejection of the U.S.-British
air strikes against Iraq and urged Arabs to take a decisive stand
to end the assault. 
</P>
</TEXT>
