<HEADLINE> Plane Crash Victims in Tanzania Identified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The 10 tourists from the
United States, together with a pilot and a tourist guide, who were
killed in a plane crash in northern Tanzania's Arusha Region, have
been identified.
</P>
<P>
The dead Americans have been identified as Mr. and Mrs.
Bowersock, Ms B. Hoffman, Ms V. Cox, Mr. R. Ennis, Mr. C.Ennis,
Mr. and Mrs. Putterman, Mr. N. Dolan and Ms. M. Riffuti, reports
from Arusha said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 12 people were killed after their light aircraft crashed
Wednesday morning in the Mount Meru Forest Reserve in Arumeru
District, some 20 kilometers from Arusha municipality.
</P>
<P>
Efforts of policemen, rescue teams and several tour companies
to collect the remains in the dense forest proved completely
futile because of bad weather on Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
However, the weather improved Thursday and eyewitnesses said
that the bodies were badly damaged but were assembled ready to be
transported to the Mount Meru Hospital Mortuary.
</P>
<P>
The Cessna 404 plane, belonging to the Arusha-based Northern
Air Charter Company, went down at about 11 a.m. local time
(0800GMT) before it touched down at the Kilimanjaro International
Airport on its way to Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. tourists, after two days of game viewing at the
world-famous Serengeti National Park, were scheduled to go to the
Maasai Mara Game Reserve in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses said the crash was probably caused by poor
visibility. The pilot of the fateful plane, Christopher Pereira,
had radioed another charter plane following him, with a group of
seven Americans, alerting them of poor weather but seconds later
the communication was suddenly cut off.
</P>
<P>
The eyewitnesses said the 14-seat plane was destroyed beyond
recognition save for one engine and a propeller, while dismembered
bodies were flung as far as 500 meters from the crash site, mainly
due to the impact of the crash.
</P>
<P>
A villager who joined the rescue team said some small pieces of
human flesh were seeing hanging down the trees.
</P>
<P>
The work of the rescue was made difficult because of the thick
forest covered with cypress trees and wild animals in the area.
</P>
<P>
The Arusha Regional Police Commander, Juma Ng' wanang' waka,
was at the crash site on Thursday afternoon together with the
Directorate of Civil Aviation (DCA) officials.
</P>
<P>
The other Tanzanian, who was killed in the crash, has been
identified as Mr. William Meiriali, a guide with the Abercrombie
and Kent tourism firm, which arranged the tour of 17 American
tourists.
</P>
<P>
But the other seven who were travelling in another light plane
landed safely at the Kilimanjaro International Airport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
