<HEADLINE> IDB to Strengthen Government Services in Jamaica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) announced Thursday the approval of a loan
of 35 million U.S. dollars to Jamaica to strengthen the capacity
of local governments to finance and manage basic services and to
maintain infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The resources will assist the implementation of the Local
Governments Reform Program, continuing and expanding efforts now
under way to rehabilitate local infrastructure and to improve the
legal and institutional framework for local government, the
Washington-based IDB said.
</P>
<P>
The program will strengthen the capabilities of the parish
councils so that they become more efficient and accountable as
providers of services to citizens, the IDB said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, resources will be used to strengthen mechanisms
that will enhance the participation of citizens, nongovernment
organizations, and private sector entities in local economic
development planning and the delivery of services.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the program is 50 million dollars. The IDB
loan is for a 25-year term, with a five-year grace period, at the
variable annual interet rate, now 6.84 percent. Local counterpart
funds total 15 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
