<HEADLINE> Greece Announces Measures to Help Lower Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis Thursday announced measures to reduce taxes and prices on
certain goods in a bid to lower the country's inflation, which now
stands at 2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The package also includes income support for pensioners,
farmers and the unemployed, the semi-official Athens News Agency
(ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, the package entails a reduction in the special
consumer tax on heating petrol from 20,000 drachmas (about 65.6
U.S. dollars) per ton to 6,100 drachmas (about 20 dollars) per
ton.
</P>
<P>
A reduction in special consumer charges on cars is expected to
bring down prices of new cars by about 10 percent on average.
</P>
<P>
The tax-free threshold for wage-earners and pensioners will be
increased from 1.355 million drachmas (about 4,442.6 dollars) to
1.9 million drachmas (about 6,229.5 dollars) for the present tax
year, with the threshold rising further to 2.3 million drachmas
(about 7,540.9 dollars) in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment benefits are to increase by 10 percent, those
insured with the agricultural pension fund will receive an extra
10,000 drachmas (about 32.8 dollars) as of January 1, 2000 and all
unemployed regardless of age will be eligible to receive free
health care. 
</P>
</TEXT>
