mid-1998, and that the discussions "are not from an immediate
perspective but from a long-term one. Our two countries have no
choice other than to cooperate."
</P>
<P>
He said that "progress" had been made over the thorny issue of
Cahora Bassa, but declined to give any details. The main problem
here is a dispute over the price at which Cahora Bassa power
should be sold to the South African electricity company, Eskom.
</P>
<P>
Eskom is insisting on paying no more than the price negotiated
in 1988, which the dam operating company, HCB, over 80 percent of
whose shares are owned by the Portuguese state, says is completely
unrealistic and out of date. HCB wants a 50 percent rise in the
tariff, and has proposed putting the matter to international
arbitration - a move not favoured by the Mozambican government.
</P>
<P>
Salomao claimed that South Africa "supports Mozambique in
discussions over Cahora Bassa." which implies that the two African
governments are in dispute with Portugal. 
</P>
