<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Still Concerned With Security in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
continues to be gravely concerned with security conditions in East
Timor, a U.N. spokesman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After the violence Wednesday, the situation is relatively quiet
in Dili, the capital, but the new wave of violence is reaching
other areas of the territory, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
At least two East Timorese were killed Wednesday near the
compound of the United Nations Mission in East Timor (UNAMET)
which conducted a ballot on the future of the half-island on
August 30.
</P>
<P>
In a fresh wave of riots, two U.N. local staffers were killed
Thursday in Maliana, some 140 kilometers west of Dili, Eckhard
said.
</P>
<P>
The ballot, agreed upon by Indonesia, Portugal and the U.N. on
May 5, is to determine whether the majority of the 800,000 people
in the former Portuguese colony want to stay within Indonesia with
special autonomy or to go independent.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia occupied East Timor in 1975 and made it a province
the following year after Portugal's withdrawal. However the U.N.
has since called it a non-self-governing territory.
</P>
<P>
Monday's ballot saw a 98.6 percent of voter turnout and a calm
atmosphere, but violent activities followed amid speculation of
the vote in favor of the pro-independence movement. The ballot
result is expected to be announced early next week.
</P>
<P>
Security in East Timor can be restored "only by preventing
armed groups from continuing to move around and terrorize others,"
U.N. Secretary-General's special representative Ian Martin was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Martin called on the leaders of the anti-independence forces
and the Indonesian police and army "to fulfill their respective
commitments" by ordering their members not to move around with
weapons, Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
News from Lisbon and Jakarta indicated that U.N. peace-keeping
efforts in East Timor are welcome, but Eckhard said there was no
contingency planning for sending peace-keeping forces there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
