<HEADLINE> NYSE Plans to Go Public in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The New York Stock Exchange
board of directors decided Thursday to push back the timetable for
a possible initial sale to 2000 from Thanksgiving this year as it
sees the need to solve regulatory and tax issues first.
</P>
<P>
NYSE Chairman Richard Grasso said the exchange would work out a
strategic business plan to solve a number of "public policy
questions."
</P>
<P>
Grasso said in July he hoped investors would be able to buy
NYSE stocks by Thanksgiving. Another Wall Street big stock
exchange -- the NASDAQ Stock Market -- also showed its willingness
to go public.
</P>
<P>
They thought such a move would help them prevail against
fast-growing competition from electronic trading networks which
match buy and sell orders by computer in a cheaper way for
investors, rather than on a traditional trading floor.
</P>
<P>
Grasso said Thursday the NYSE may spin off its regulatory unit.
Federal Securities and Exchange Commission and exchanges officials
are in talks about how to provide for the independence of the
regulatory unit.
</P>
<P>
Whether initial public offering (IPO) members should pay
capital gains taxes on the value of their seats is another issue
to be solved.
</P>
<P>
Congress is also watching the implications of exchanges going
public. The Senate Banking Committee has scheduled a September 23
hearing on the NYSE and NASDAQ IPO plans, sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
