<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agassi, Seles, Williams Advance at U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Andre Agassi knows that it
does not take much to go from tournament favorite to early-round
loser. So he did not take any chances today against Axel Pretzsch.
</P>
<P>
Agassi dispatched the German qualifier 6-3, 6-2, 6-1 to advance
to the third round at the U.S. Open Tennis Championships in New
York.
</P>
<P>
On the women's side, two-time winner and fourth seed Monica
Seles of the United States cruised past Silvia Farina of Italy 6-2,
6-2 in 62 minutes. She won the title here in 1991 and 1992, and
appeared in the final in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Appearing in her second U.S. Open, seventh seed Serena Williams
of the United States faced a player with less experience than she
and dominated Croatian qualifier Jelena Kostanic 6-4, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Favored to win his second Grand Slam of the season since No. 1
Pete Sampras and two-time defending champion Patrick Rafter of
Australia pulled out due to injuries, Agassi never was truly
pushed during the 94-minute match.
</P>
<P>
The second-seeded American made 26 unforced errors but won 76
percent of his first-service points, hit 32 winners and converted
6-of-10 break points. He improved to 21-2 lifetime against
qualifiers at Grand Slams.
</P>
<P>
He won the Frnehc Open in June and could become the No. 1
player in the world if he goes farther in the draw than third seed
Yevgeny Kafelnikov of Russia.
</P>
<P>
In action involving men's seeds, 10th seed Marcelo Rios of
Chile overcame a slow start to get past George Bastl of
Switzerland 4-6,6-3, 6-2, 6-2; No. 12 Richard Krajicek of the
Netherlands moved into the third round with a 6-2, 6-4, 6-1 win
over Lorenzo Manta of Switzerland; and No. 15 Nicolas Kiefer of
Germany topped countryman Michael Kohlmann 6-3, 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Tonight, Michael Chang of the United States takes on Arnaud
Clement of France in a battle of unseeded players.
</P>
<P>
In the women's battles, the 25-year-old Seles took advantage of
24 unforced errors by Farina and hit 21 winners as she raised her
record at the U.S. Open to 40-6. She will face Ai Sugiyama of
Japan, who defeated Karina Habsudova of Slovakia 6-2, 4-6, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
Second seed and defending champion Lindsay Davenport of the
United States plays Dragomir of Romania tonight. Davenport cruised
past doubles partner Corina Morariu 6-0, 6-3 on Tuesday. She has
never lost to Dragomir in four all-time meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
