<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Thinking Brings Success to Miao People (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Miao ethnic minority
people in southwest China's Guizhou Province are ridding
themselves of the outdated notion that "one ought not leave their
hometown no matter how poor," and many of them are now earning a
good living in other places.
</P>
<P>
The Miao people of the Miao-Dong Qiandongnan Autonomous
Prefecture once dared not make friends with the Han people because
they had been ill-treated by the Kuomintang troops before the
founding of New China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
They were forced to give up their folk costumes and their own
language, and the Kuomintang soldiers would cut short the hair of
the Miao women.
</P>
<P>
But now it is a common sight to see Miao people intermarry with
other ethnic groups, and some families are made up of three or
four different ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
The central government has also provided opportunities for
ethnic minorities to become better trained. Over 1,300 Miao
officials in the province had been sent to colleges by the year
1956 when the prefecture was established.
</P>
<P>
And now, one-third of all prefecture officials, or more than 20,
000, are Miaos.
</P>
<P>
Miao people used to think that they could only survive by
farming, even though 80 percent of them could not even feed
themselves by just working on the farm before the founding of New
China.
</P>
<P>
Now, however, the 1.57 million Miao people in the prefecture no
longer worry about how they will eat tomorrow, as more and more
Miaos have left their hometowns to enter business elsewhere since
the implementation of the opening-up and reform policies two
decades ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Thinking Brings Success to Miao People (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thousands of Miao women in a county of Kaili City, the first
place with regional autonomy for minorities, have left their
hometown to sell folk-style jewelry, and many of them have gone as
far as Myanmar and Russia.
</P>
<P>
There are some 40,000 to 50,000 young people of Sansui County,
another place mainly inhabited by Miaos, working outside the
county, and many of them return with money and skills and start
their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
Incomplete statistics show that the county's young workers now
earn a total of over 100 million yuan ( about 12 million U.S.
dollars) a year, and remittance back to the county is more than 30
million yuan, twice that of the annual revenue for the whole
county.
</P>
<P>
The Miao people have also learned to earn a living by
exploiting their special customs and traditions. Foe example,
there are some 39 Miao traditional living compounds in Qiandongnan
Prefecture that have been developed into tourist attractions.
</P>
<P>
Folk dances, wonderful folk music, and special costumes and
houses are attracting many tourists, and every household in one of
the compounds, called Langde, for example, will earn over 20,000
yuan a year.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture has been named one of the top ten ethnic
minority cultural tourism attractions in the world by the United
Nations Folk Culture Fund for its spectacular customs and natural
scenery.
</P>
<P>
The Miao ethnic minority now live mostly in the southeastern
part of Guizhou, in south China's Guangxi and Hainan provinces,
and in the border areas of the Hunan, Hubei, Sichuan, and Yuannan
provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
