<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Tibetan Medicine Doctor (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAHSA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Luo Yu, a 60-year old road
worker, made a special trip to express his deep thanks to Aduo, a
Tibetan doctor in the village of Luelang in southwest China's
Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Luo wouldn't have recovered without the Tibetan medicine, he
told the 56-year old doctor. Luo had suffered from gall-stones for
a year before getting Aduo's help earlier this year. A recent
examination showed that the gall-stones had disappeared completely.
</P>
<P>
Luelang lies in a valley where for generations Tibetans have
had a reputation for the use of leeches to treat ailments and Aduo
began learning Tibetan medicine at the age of 8.
</P>
<P>
In the past, both serf owners and serfs came to them for
treatment, he said, and they were very busy but got little pay.
Sometimes they were even beaten by the serf owners and had to make
a living however they could.
</P>
<P>
After New China was established, Aduo and other Tibetan doctors
were given land but were also encouraged to develop traditional
Tibetan medicine, and doctors in the village now use 250 kinds of
herbal medicines and have developed more than 100 kinds of
traditional Tibetan medicines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Tibetan Medicine Doctor (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Earlier this year, Ceringmar, a local herdsman, complained of
having been sick for months with a cold and fever, but he was able
to resume his work after 2 months of treatment by Aduo.
</P>
<P>
There are six people in Audo's family. His children study or
work in other places outside the village. The family's annual
average income is more than 10,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the humid climate in the county caused a serious skin
disease to spread, affecting hundreds of people and Western
medicine didn't seem to help.
</P>
<P>
But, Aduo developed a medicine from herbs and minerals and
cured most of the patients. More recently, he developed a new
medicine to treat bronchitis in children and 400 Tibetan children
were cured.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan medicine is an important part of traditional Chinese
medicine, Audo said, and he is determined to continue research and
development in his field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
