<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Striving to Become Key Int'l City (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The city has since shifted its focus of development from the
processing industry to finance, trade, information technology, and
other new and high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that Shanghai achieved 368.8 billion
yuan in gross domestic product (GDP) in 1998, and its per capita
GDP topped 28,000 yuan, ranking the first in the country.
</P>
<P>
Of the total volume, about half came from the major industries
of automobiles, iron and steel, telecommunications, mechanical and
electrical equipment, chemicals, and electric home appliances, and
16 percent from the sectors of integrated circuitry and computers,
pharmaceuticals, and new materials.
</P>
<P>
A series of State-level exchanges have been established in
Shanghai, including the Shanghai Stock Exchange, the Shanghai
Futures Exchange, and the China Foreign Exchange Trade System.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of overseas business people have shown
keen interest in investing in Shanghai, and so far some 20,000
overseas-funded businesses have been operational, with a combined
contractual investment of 37 billion U.S. dollars. And 59 of the
top 100 multinational firms in the world have made investment in
the city.
</P>
<P>
In the coming years, Xu said, Shanghai will open up wider to
the outside world and take a more active part in the global
economy, while continuing its market-oriented reforms.
</P>
<P>
And more capital and talented people will be introduced from
abroad, the mayor said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
