<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0383 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Factsheet (5): Key Political Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 3 (Xinhua) --
</P>
<P>
The Indian National Congress:
</P>
<P>
The Congress, founded in 1885 to oppose British rule, has ruled
India for around 45 of the 50 years since independence in 1947.
</P>
<P>
Jawahar Lal Nehru ruled India as its first prime minister at
the head of a Congress government from 1947 to 1964.
</P>
<P>
Indira Gandhi, Nehru's daughter, headed the country's Congress
government twice from 1966 to 1977 and from 1980 to 1984 when she
was killed by her body guard.
</P>
<P>
Rajiv Gandhi replaced his mother as Congress leader and prime
minister in 1984 and he was assassinated in 1989 by a suicide
bomb.
</P>
<P>
From 1991 to 1996, a minority Congress government took office
and won over enough members of parliament to attain a majority
after two years.
</P>
<P>
The party got only 141 seats in the 545-member low house of
parliament in the 1998 elections. In order to prevent the Indian
People's Party (BJP) from coming to power, the Congress, which
could not come to power itself, decided to offer its support from
outside to the UF which then formed a coalition government.
</P>
<P>
On March 16, 1998, Sonia Gandhi, who was appointed new
president of the Congress Party on March 14, was unanimously
elected as chairperson of the Congress Parliamentary Party.
</P>
<P>
The Congress in its 1999 election manifesto pledged to provide
a "stable, able and experienced government" if it were elected in
the coming Lok Sabha elections.
</P>
<P>
The Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP, Indian People's Party):
</P>
<P>
The Bharatiya Janata Party, founded in 1980 as a breakaway
group of the People's party, is the largest parliamentary party in
India. The BJP got its first taste of power at the national level
after the inconclusive 1996 elections during which the party won
193 seats with its alliance. Its government, however, fell within
a fortnight after failing to establish a majority in the hung
parliament.
</P>
<P>
During the 1998 elections, the BJP obtained 182 seats in the
Lower House of parliament and on March 19, 1998, Atal Bihari
Vajpayee, leader of BJP, was sworn-in as Indian prime Minister at
the head of a two-tied 43 member coalition which included a number
of new faces.
</P>
<P>
On April 17, 1999, the 13-month Vajpayee coalition government
was defeated by one vote in the vote of confidence in the Lower
House of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
In its manifesto of 1999 election, the BJP-led National
Democratic Alliance pledged to continue the reform process to
ensure that the national economy grow on the principle that "India
shall be built by Indians."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0384 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Factsheet (6): Brief History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- India is one of the
countries with an ancient civilization in the world. It became a
unified country in 4th century BC.
</P>
<P>
European colonists began to invade India in the 16th century.
The Pulasi War between India and Britain broke out in 1757. India
was defeated and became a British colony. Britain occupied all the
territory of India in 1849.
</P>
<P>
An uprising against the British by the Indian people took place
in 1857.
</P>
<P>
In June 1947, Britain promulgated "Mountbatten Plan", which
divided India into India and Pakistan. After a prolonged struggle
against British colonial rule, India became independent within the
commonwealth on August 15, 1947. In November 1949, the Constituent
Assembly approved a republican Constitution, providing for a
president as head of state.
</P>
<P>
India became republic on January 26, 1950, although remaining a
member of the commonwealth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0385 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Considers Converting Vehicles Into Natural Gas Users </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
considering converting all its vehicles to compressed-natural gas
(CNG) users and establishing CNG filling stations across the
country to combat air pollution, The Bangladesh Observer reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Officials were quoted as saying that an inter-ministerial
meeting recently decided that a formal proposal would be presented
to the Establishment Ministry in consultation with the Environment
Ministry, and another proposal to the Dhaka Urban Transport
Authority and Air Quality Management Project to bring all the
three-stroke engine vehicles under the CNG program.
</P>
<P>
The issue of expanding CNG use will be placed in the next
meeting of the National Environment Council, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also decided to encourage the state-owned
Bangladesh Road Transport Corporation (BRTC) to go for plying
gas-fueled "dedicated engine" buses, following a positive response
from the BRTC.
</P>
<P>
A BRTC representative said they got a good result in running
buses with natural gas on experimental basis and the cost didn't
widely vary in comparison with diesel-engine buses.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,050 vehicles have been transformed into CNG-users since
the government initiated the program about 10 years ago to protect
the environment from diesel and petrol and save foreign exchange,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Air pollution in the Bangladeshi capital has reached a very
high level due to emission of suspended particulate materials by
pollution vehicles at an increasing rate, according to a survey
conducted by the Department of Environment on the air quality in
the city.
</P>
<P>
About 160,000 motorized vehicles are operating in Dhaka
metropolitan area at present, with about one-third of them having
no fitness certificates, according to the Bangladesh Road
Transport Authority.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
