<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0395 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of India's political Events (2): </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 3 (Xinhua) --
</P>
<P>
In January 1980, a general election to the House of the People
was held. The Indian National Congress received 42.7 percent of
the total votes and won an overwhelming majority (352) of the
elective seats. Indira Gandhi was reinstated as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
In 1983 and 1984, disturbances occurred in Jammu and Kashmir
during local elections.
</P>
<P>
In October 1984, Indira Gandhi was assassinated by militant
Sikh members of her personal guards. Her son, Rajiv Gandhi, was
immediately sworn in as prime minister. The widespread communal
violence that erupted throughout India, resulting in more than
2,000 deaths, was curbed by the prompt action of the government.
</P>
<P>
In the January 1985 election polling, the Indian National
Congress received 49.2 percent of the total votes and won 403 of
the 513 contested seats.
</P>
<P>
In February 1986, there were mass demonstrations and strikes
throughout India in protest against the government-imposed
increases of the prices of basic commodities.
</P>
<P>
In June 1986, Laldenga, the leader of the Mizo National Front
(MNF), signed a peace agreement with Rajiv Gandhi, thus ending
Mizoram's 25 years of rebellion.
</P>
<P>
During 1987, the Indian National Congress experienced serious
political setbacks. It sustained defeats in a number of state
elections, and political tensions were intensified by an open
dispute between the prime minister and the outgoing president,
Giani Zail Singh.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, a more confrontational style was adopted by the
central administration towards non-Indian National Congress state
governments, and presidential rule was imposed in states suffering
political instability.
</P>
<P>
In November 1989, the Indian National Congress lost its overall
majority (193 of the 525) in the general election to the House of
the People. On December 2, after the National Front promised the
support of the communist parties and the BJP, V.P. Singh was sworn
in as the new prime minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0396 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
