<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of India's Political Events (3): </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 3 (Xinhua) --
</P>
<P>
In November 1990, one of the prime minister's leading rivals in
the Janata Dal, Chandra Shekhar, formed his own dissident faction,
known as the Janata Dal (Socialist) or Janata Dal (S) (which
merged with the Janata party in April 1991 to become the Samajwadi
Party). And he was sworn in as prime minister on November 10,
1990.
</P>
<P>
On May 21, 1991, after the first day of the general election,
Rajiv Gandhi was assassinated. The remaining election was
postponed until mid-June. The final result gave Indian National
Congress 227 of the 511 seats contested, the BJP won 119 seats.
</P>
<P>
On January 16, 1993, Prime Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao's
59-member Cabinet resigned to make for a new set of ministers to
help deal with the religious crisis (at least 70 more people there
died in Muslim-Hindu clashes).
</P>
<P>
On December 22, 1994, the health minister, the food minister
and a junior development minister resigned from their posts after
being accused of official corruption (participating in commodities
and stock market scams).
</P>
<P>
On October 28, 1995, President Shankar Dayal Sharma dissolved
the Uttar Pradesh State legislature on the recommendation of Prime
Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao and imposed federal rule. The
Legislature's dismissal was to keep the BJP from forming a new
government ahead of the elections and establishing a political
grip there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0398 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
