<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some 15,000 Congolese Refugees Enter Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
agreed to provide assistance to some 15,000 Congolese refugees who
have entered Mporokoso, a northern province of Zambia, as a result
of the instability in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
A statement from the European Union (EU) released in Lusaka
Thursday confirmed the movement of the refugees, according to a
report by Times of Zambia newspaper Friday.
</P>
<P>
In addition to administrative and logistical support for
Zambia's Refugee Commission, multi-sectoral assistance would be
provided to improve the living conditions of the affected
populations, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said road access network to the camp would be improved along
with the health services, provision of safe water, construction of
latrines, management of distribution and reception of refugees at
the refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
Non-food essential items such as soap, kitchen sets and
blankets would further be provided and logistical support be
bolstered through the provision of transport and communications,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said the assistance would also cover a contingency plan for
an additional 20,000 refugees should this become necessary.
</P>
<P>
The funding would cover the requirements of the United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and its implementing
partners from June until the end of the year, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
