<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of India's political Events (4): </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 3 (Xinhua) --
</P>
<P>
In late April and early May 1996, a general election was held.
The largest party in terms of seats was the BJP, which won 160
seats. While the Indian National Congress gained 136 seats, the
National Front and Left Front together obtained 179 seats.
</P>
<P>
On May 15, President Shankar Dayal Sharma appointed Atal Bihari
Vajpayee as prime minister to form a new government, which
resigned ahead of a parliamentary confidence vote that was
virtually certain to be negative on May 28.
</P>
<P>
On June 12, the new United Front coalition government of Prime
Minister Deve Gowda, appointed by the president on May 28, won a
vote of confidence in the Parliament, ending a period of
administrative paralysis since the May election.
</P>
<P>
On July 25, 1997, Kocheril Raman Narayanan, a member of
Hinduism's lowest caste, was sworn in as president. He earned
about 95 percent of the 5,000 votes on July 14.
</P>
<P>
On December 2, President Narayanan dissolved the Parliament and
announced the parliamentary election would be held in February
1998.
</P>
<P>
From February 16, 1998, India started its general elections and
after three phases of polling on February 16, 22, and 28, the
election process in most of the country's 545 constituencies had
been virtually concluded on March 7. The Bharatiya Janata party
(BJP) and the Indian National Congress, the two major national
political parties, got 182 and 141 of 545 seats respectively.
</P>
<P>
On March 16, Sonia Gandhi, new president of the Congress Party,
was unanimously elected chairperson of the Congress Parliamentary
Party.
</P>
<P>
On March 19, Atal Bihari Vajpayee, leader of the BJP was sworn
in as Indian prime minister at the head of a two-tied 43-member
coalition which included a number of new faces.
</P>
<P>
On April 17, 1999, the BJP-led government resigned immediately
after losing the vote of confidence by 269 to 270 in the House of
the People. President Narayanan asked Prime Minister Vajpayee to
continue as caretaker till alternative arrangements were made.
</P>
<P>
On April 26, India's caretaker cabinet headed by Vajpayee
decided to recommend to President Narayanan to dissolve the lower
house of parliament as no political party and its allies could be
able to provide a stable majority government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
