<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Help S. Africa's Neighbors Cope With Free </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
is ready to provide aid for South Africa's neighbors to shield
them from the adverse impact of the EU-South African free trade
deal, a visiting EU trade official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, Philip Lowe, director-general for development in the
EU, said the promised financial support, in the form of budgetary
support, was not compensation, Business Day reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
A study by the South African Foundation has estimated that the
scrapping of tariffs on EU imports could shave as much as 3.5
billion rand (574 million U.S. dollars) off government revenues
for South Africa's neighbors.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Southern African Customs Union partners --
Namibia, Botswana, Lesotho and Swaziland -- depend heavily on
their large share of the pooled revenue from tariffs on European
goods.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho and Swaziland each derive over 40 percent of their
total government revenue from the pool.
</P>
<P>
The EU-South African free trade deal is expected to be
implemented in January next year. The deal promises to free as
much as 90 percent of bilateral trade in 12 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
