<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rapid Increase of Breast Cancer Incidence in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The incidence of breast
cancer in Asia, though lower than in Europe and America, is
apparently increasing rapidly, epidemiologists told an on-going
international cancer seminar in Tianjin today.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 specialists and scholars from 14 countries and
regions are attending the second Asian Seminar on Breast Cancer in
this port city in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
The specialists attribute the rise to the overall improvement
of living standards in Asia over recent years.
</P>
<P>
In China, the growth rate of such cancer in the ten major
cities has averaged 37 percent, according to the epidemiologist
with Shanghai experiencing the highest figures of 26.5 cases per
100,000 women, followed by Beijing and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Medical experts say that some 1.2 million women around the
world suffer from breast cancer, a common disease among women, and
500,000 of them will die from it every year. Growth rates around
the world vary between 5 to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Epidemiologists note that physical factors, biological
conditions, the environment, and intake of protein, may all
attribute to the increase. And they believe that a longer
menstrual period, first births over 35 years of age and short
breast feeding periods are the most probable causes.
</P>
<P>
Increased intakes of high fat, low fiber food, but little fruit
and vegetables in the daily diet may also lead to the disease.
</P>
<P>
They say that making more information about the disease widely
known, recommending a more practical diet, breast feeding, and a
healthier life style will play an important role in preventing and
controlling the disease.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
