<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0428 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Ready to Expand Cooperation With UNDP: Minister (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since China restored its seat at the United Nations in 1971, it
has actively made contributions to the development programs of the
UN. But it refused to take contributions from the UNDP, even after
the deadly earthquake in Tangshan, northern China's Hebei Province,
one of the worst in history, that killed 240,000 people.
</P>
<P>
China's refusal to accept such aid continued until it adopted
the reform and opening policy in 1978. "In September 1979, the
UNDP established its Beijing representative office, marking the
beginning of a new phase of cooperation," according to the Shi.
</P>
<P>
"This effective cooperation has helped expand relations between
China and international organizations on a mutually beneficial
basis, introduced new technology and trained specialized
professionals for China," Shi said.
</P>
<P>
"With limited capital, the UNDP has played a unique role in the
reform and opening drive and economic construction of a country
that has a vast territory and a huge population," he said. "This
fully demonstrates that the UNDP's assistance is effective."
</P>
<P>
Nay Htun, assistant Administrator of the UNDP, said, "The
cooperation between the UNDP and China is excellent and has
produced some very important results as it was built on mutual
trust."
</P>
<P>
During a recent meeting between Chinese President Jiang Zemin
and visiting UNDP Administrator Mark Brown, the two sides agreed
to continue to work and be focused on poverty elimination,
environmental protection, to bring in new knowledge, new
technology and new management approaches, according to Kerstin
Leitner, resident representative of the UNDP in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
