<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-National Day Special Urbanites In China Living More Comfortable Lives (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Editor's note: This year is
the 50th anniversary of the People's Republic of China. The past
five decades of achievements in the economy have attracted the
attention of the rest of the world. Xinhua started a series of
stories on the nation's economy on August 17. This is the 14th.
</P>
<P>
The Statistics Bureau reports that, by United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) standards, China's urban dwellers
are leading comfortable lives.
</P>
<P>
By FAO standards, an Engel coefficient (based on the percentage
of income spent on food) above 60 percent means a poor life, 60 to
50 percent means a life without food worries, 50 to 40 percent
means a comfortable life, and below 40 percent a rich life. China'
s dropped to 45 percent in 1998 for urban families.
</P>
<P>
Living a more comfortable life has been the dream of ordinary
Chinese for generations, but they have been visited by nightmare
all through this century, with starvation and death becoming a
part of people's daily lives.
</P>
<P>
In 1948, a quarter of Beijing's residents, 250,000 people, were
struggling with poverty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
