<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's "Power Tiger" Bows to Market Law (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Last year, China became the third-largest power producer in the
world, generating a total of 1.160 trillion kwh of electricity,
and the country's hydraulic power sector is now world's largest,
followed by the United States.
</P>
<P>
Gao Yan, general manager of the State Power Company, attributes
the power surplus to the rapid expansion of the power industry,
and this new situation has produced many new problems for the
industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
Many domestic and foreign experts point out that the present
difficulty in selling electricity is not a result of oversupply,
but rather an indication of low consumption.
</P>
<P>
In China, the average monthly consumption of electricity for
urban families is 100 to 200 kwh, only one-tenth of the average of
urbanites in developed nations.
</P>
<P>
To cope with this situation, governments at all levels have
worked out many favorable polices to encourage customers to
increase electricity consumption.
</P>
<P>
Many urbanites have found they no long need to hesitate on
whether or not to use high energy-consuming appliances such as
electric oven and irons. The former policy of extra charges for
over-consumption has been replaced with "the more electricity you
use, the cheaper the prices become."
</P>
<P>
For decades, rural people had to pay their electricity bills at
rates much higher than their urban counterparts because, it was
said, the farmers should pay for the building costs. No one had
ever explained why the State only paid the building cost for urban
residents.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, however, villagers are glad to see that the price of
power has been cut to an level equivalent to that enjoyed by city
dwellers.
</P>
<P>
The constant development of the power industry has also been
placed on the top of the central government's agenda. While
efforts are being made to shut down small power stations with
generating capacities of 50,000 kw and below, the plans to build
more large power plants, mainly hydraulic ones, have never been
put aside.
</P>
<P>
The central government continues to restructure the power
industry by separating the management of power stations and power-
supply networks to lay a foundation for the future formation of a
unified, national network.
</P>
<P>
In the next three years, China will invest 260 billion yuan in
rebuilding both urban and rural power-supply networks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0440 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Eyes Investment From APEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada is determined to win investments for the country during
his upcoming trip to New Zealand for the informal leadership
conference of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC), a top
official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said the president wants to
give the Philippine economy a much-needed boost with his APEC
stint, as well as his visit to Latin America following the
conference.
</P>
<P>
"The president will leave by the end of the week for Auckland
to attend the APEC summit and proceed to Chile and Argentina,"
Zamora said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Estrada said he hopes to attract much-needed
foreign investments that will spur economic growth and create jobs
for people.
</P>
<P>
The president said he would seek investments during his
meetings with leaders of other APEC economies, which include the
United States.
</P>
<P>
"We will seek help during the APEC summit to revitalize
business and the economy," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Following his attendance at APEC's informal leadership
conference in New Zealand, Estrada will proceed to Latin America
for state visits in Chile and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
In his first APEC stint as president in 1998 in Malaysia,
Estrada was designated as spokesman for the poor members of APEC.
</P>
<P>
Upon his initiative, the 20 other leaders of APEC economies
agreed to adopt social safety nets to help poorer nations cope
with the Asian economies crisis.
</P>
<P>
More affluent countries such as the United States and Japan
also started their own initiatives to extend financial assistance
to countries hit by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Among these initiatives are the 30-billion-U.S.-dollar Miyazawa
package for hard-hit economies, and the 10-billion-dollar joint
initiative by the United States and Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
