<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana to Recall Parliament for Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A state of emergency has
been declared in Botswana for recalling parliament to allow 60,000
more voters to participate in the general elections, South
Africa's Business Day newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The parliament was dissolved in July before the elections
scheduled for October 16 begin.
</P>
<P>
President Festus Mogae announced Thursday that he was declaring
the emergency for the sole purpose of being able to recall the
parliament in accordance with the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
The Electoral Act could then be amended to permit the
Independent Electoral Commission (IEC) to complete its work.
</P>
<P>
The 60,000 voters, who had registered during a supplementary
registration exercise, were not included in the voters' roll.
</P>
<P>
Legal problems arose last week when the president issued a writ
for the elections to be held on October 16. At that time, new
certified voters' rolls had not been completed.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, opposition parties called for the
resignation of senior IEC staff following the disqualification of
the 60,000 registered voters.
</P>
<P>
The opposition has accused the government of incompetence in
preparing for the elections.
</P>
<P>
Botswana has a population of 1.5 million, of which 900,000 are
eligible for the election. Some 460,000, or 51 percent, of the
eligible voters have registered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
