<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0448 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-National Day special Urbanites In China Living More Comfortable Lives (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Now, the symbol of wealth is the telephone, mobile phone, air-
conditioner, personal computer, and car.
</P>
<P>
By 1998, there were 105 color TVs for every 100 urban families,
91 washing machines, 76 refrigerators, 76 telephones, 20 air-
conditioners, 4 computers and 0.25 cars.
</P>
<P>
Urban housing has improved remarkably over the past two decades.
In 1981, only 14 percent of urban families had more than 8 square
meters of living space for each member. The figure rose to 48
percent in 1988 and to 77 percent in 1998. In 1981, as much as 37
percent of urban families did not have their own house, or had
less than 4 square meters of living space for each member. The
figure now only 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Perhaps the figure that speaks the loudest is that of bank
deposits. In 1952, individual bank deposits amounted to only 900
million yuan. That figure began to increase at an incredible rate
after 1978, when it was 21 billion yuan to 233.8 billion yuan by
1986. By the end of 1998, Chinese banks held 5.34 trillion yuan in
individual deposits, a 254-fold increase from 1978. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0449 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 09:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Tourists Jailed for Possession of Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Five British tourists were
jailed Thursday for one month in Cyprus after pleading guilty to
possessing a small quantity of hard drugs, local mass media
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
They were identified as Natasha Wright and Mark Alexander
Lambie, both 26, Josef Jacobs Green, 43, Errol O'Neil Gordon and
Richard Samuels, 27.
</P>
<P>
Police said they all were from London.
</P>
<P>
"The possession and use of drugs by foreign tourists in Cyprus
has grown to worrying proportions and the imposition of prison
sentences has become inevitable," said Judge Leonidas Kalogirou.
</P>
<P>
The five were arrested in Cyprus' southeast Ayia Napa town on
August 28, following a search of three apartments where they were
staying.
</P>
<P>
The search found five ecstasy pills and a small bag of cannabis.
</P>
<P>
The five admitted to buying the drugs from a dealer in Ayia
Napa.
</P>
<P>
Drug squad officers are trying to track down a narcotics gang
who they believe supply illegal substances to British tourists in
Ayia Napa.
</P>
<P>
Over 1 million British tourists are expected to visit Cyprus
this year, with most flocking to Ayia Napa's club scene. 
</P>
</TEXT>
