<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Bank Buys 19 Billion Yuan in T-Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Construction Bank of China
announced here today that it would buy 19 billion yuan of the 60
billion yuan supplementary treasury bonds newly issued by the
Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
The bank said it has already paid for 60 percent of the bonds,
while the remaining 40 percent would be paid for by September 8.
</P>
<P>
China's National People's Congress approved the issue of a 60
billion yuan supplementary treasury bonds recently, in a bid to
further stimulate domestic consumption and investment.
</P>
<P>
Proceeds from the bonds are expected to be spent on ongoing
infrastructure projects, technical upgrading projects in major
industrial sectors, environmental protection projects, and
increasing pensions and the salary of civil servants.
</P>
<P>
Among China's four major state-owned commercial banks, the
Construction Bank is the second largest investor in the said
treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
Its officials said the 10 year term bonds are a safe investment
and would help the bank improve its structure of financial assets,
as it is the first time a floating interest rate has been applied
to treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
As the 60 billion yuan bonds would require 254 billion yuan in
supporting bank loans, the bank said it would increase its
investment to related industrial sectors in recognition of the
government policy.
</P>
<P>
They disclosed that the Construction Bank is reviewing 1,000 or
more projects recommended by the government and has already
pledged to lend 5.5 billion yuan to the chosen projects.
</P>
<P>
The bank is also reviewing more than 100 other projects of its
choice and has signed preliminary lending agreements with them.
</P>
</TEXT>
