<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Makes Efforts Fighting Drug Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is making efforts to
cure drug addicts and fight drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
More than 12,300 drug addicts have so far this year received
medical treatment at centers and within communities and families
in accordance with the guidelines of Vietnam's Ministry of Labor,
War Invalids and Social Affairs, according to a report of Vietnam
News Agency on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Almost all detoxification centers have extended treatment time
from three to six months or even a year and have built more
facilities to treat more addicts.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to fight drug abuse among young people, Vietnam's
Ministry of Education and Training has coordinated with relevant
agencies and local authorities in taking measures of various
kinds.
</P>
<P>
However, nearly 90 percent of Vietnam's 97,000 drug addicts and
8,000 drug-addicted prisoners have failed to respond to treatment
and the number of relapsed victims accounts for 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
To effectively cure drug addicts, Vietnam's Ministry of Public
Health has asked relevant agencies to speed up the research,
evaluation and experiments of traditional medicines and
acupuncture in treatment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0460 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Works for East Asian Cooperation Relationship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia said Friday that
the framework for cooperation and working relationship among East
Asian countries should be well structured.
</P>
<P>
"Working together in the next century on East Asian basis has
to be structured in a way that will detail serious discussions,"
Malaysian International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz
told reporters after meeting with a Japanese mission for
revitalization of Asian Economy here.
</P>
<P>
She said that among the areas that could be worked on are the
reform of the financial system, on how to strengthen the regional
economy, working together to affect more optimum flow of resources
within the East Asian region and how to enable the region to
become a very viable market.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has always voiced out the need for such cooperation
through the formation of East Asia Economic Caucus (EAEC), which
Japan was in favor of, Rafidah said.
</P>
<P>
She said if there was an established and well structured East
Asia entity, then the concept of the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA)
to be implemented by the year 2003 could be expanded to the East
Asia Free Trade Area.
</P>
<P>
Such idea is not against the World Trade Organization but
feasible as free trade would allow East Asian countries to have
more liberal flows of goods and services within the region, she
said.
</P>
<P>
Touching on the reform of international financial architecture,
she said: "Putting our heads together in East Asia, we can get our
experts to think what kind of strategies, what kind of measures we
can suggest to the authorities to shape or reshape the financial
structure on a global basis." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
