<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of President Jiang Zemin's Speech in Thailand (Part One) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The following is the full text
of Chinese President Jiang Zemin's speech at the National Cultural
Center of the Kingdom of Thailand on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Enhance Good-Neighbourliness and Friendship
</P>
<P>
And Build a Better Future Together
</P>
<P>
Your Royal Highness Princess Sirindhorn,
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Bhichai Rattakul,
</P>
<P>
Mr. Director,
</P>
<P>
Ladies and Gentlemen,
</P>
<P>
I am honored to be here with you and address you today at the
invitation of the International Studies Center of the Ministry of
Foreign Affairs of Thailand. At the outset, I wish to extend, on
behalf of the Chinese Government and people and also in my own
name, our cordial greetings and best wishes to the people of
Thailand and our heartfelt thanks to all those, present or not,
who have helped enhance the friendship between our two peoples.
</P>
<P>
We are delighted to see the further development of the time-
honored China-Thailand relations over the last quarter of this
century. Cooperation between our two countries has been effective
and productive in all fields. A line from the song "the Chinese
and the Thais are brothers" has expressed the common will of our
two peoples. His Majesty King Bhumibol Adulyadej and members of
the royal family have made outstanding contributions to the
friendship between our two countries. On the occasion of the 72nd
birthday of His Majesty, I would like to extend my best wishes to
His Majesty. The Chinese Government attaches high importance to
its relations with Thailand and regards your country as one of our
most important cooperation partners in this region. May Thailand
enjoy prosperity! May CHina-Thailand relations last forever and
become more and more important as time goes by, like the porcelain
masterpiece "Sangkhalok: jointly made by Chinese and Thai
craftsmen in ancient times!
</P>
<P>
The Asian civilization has been created and developed by the
Asian people, Chinese and Thais included. Standing at the
threshold of a new century, mankind is about to usher in a new
millennium. As we look back on the changes in the past 100 years
in Asia and into its future of hopes and challenges at this
important historical moment, all sorts of feelings well up in our
mind.
</P>
<P>
The 100-year history of Asia in the 20th century is a splendid
epic poem depicting the heroic, persevering and unyielding
struggle by the Asia people against colonialism and imperialism
and for national independence and liberation. It is also an
imposing scroll of the Asian people working hard in an
enterprising spirit to gradually lift themselves out of poverty
and backwardness and standing rock firm in the family of nations
of the world. Since the end of World War II, Asian countries,
through tenacious struggle, have stepped onto the international
arena as independent and equal members of the international
community and made significant contribution to world peace and
development. In the last 20 years or so, Asia, East Asia in
particular, with its rapid economic growth, has become one of the
most dynamic regions in the world. The drastic changes and the
rise of Asia represent a great miracle performed by Asian people
as well as an important symbol of the development and progress of
the world in the 20th century. The Chinese Government resumed the
exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong in 1997 and Macao will come
back to the embrace of the motherland as of 20 December this year.
This marks the complete conclusion of the Western colonial rule in
Asia. We are very proud of glories that Asia has won in the 20th
century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0464 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of President Jiang Zemin's Speech in Thailand (Part Two) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
National Independence and unification are important
prerequisites for the great success of Asian countries. Having
suffered enormously from imperialist invasion and bullying and
from the disintegration of their countries and families, the Asian
people have cherished dearly the hard-won national independence
and unity. It is the sacred right of the Asian peoples to
safeguard national dignity and state sovereignty, choose
independently their own social system, road to development and way
of life and reject external intervention in their internal affairs.
It is also the basic guarantee for the prosperity of Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
Self-confidence, self-respect, self-reliance and self-
improvement are important Asian spirit that has encouraged the
Asian people to go in for changes and reform and remove all
obstacles and difficulties. And it is this spirit that has
enabled the Asian people to achieve success one after another in
their economic, scientific and cultural development and nation-
building endeavour. When faced with the impact of the financial
crisis, the Thai people called on the Thais to help Thailand pull
through the hard times and stabilize the economy. Likewise in
China, when faced with last year's devastating floods rarely seen
in history, the whole nation fought courageously and unremittingly
together, winning the war against the floods. All these are vivid
expressions of the Asian spirit of Self-improvement.
</P>
<P>
Most Asian countries belong to the Third World. They
experienced the same bitter sufferings in the past and all aspire
to development now. They all know full well the importance of
treating each other as equals, conducting mutually beneficial
cooperation and living in harmony with each other. It is exactly
for this reason that the well-known Five Principles of Peaceful
Coexistence were born on the land of Asia. These norms governing
international relations accord with both the fundamental interests
of the Asia people and the demands of our times. In following
these norms, Asian counties have set up a good example for the
peaceful coexistence by countries with different social systems
and for the friendly relations and cooperation among developing
countries, which has had a far-reaching impact on the
international community as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Asia's historical experience has greatly enlightened us on how
to work out a blueprint for the new century. The growing trend
towards multi-polarisation of the world and economic globalisation,
together with the rapid advancement of science and technology and
the quiet rise of knowledge economy have brought about both new
hopes and new challenges to the development of the world including
Asia. At the threshold of the now century, the Asian people are
thinking about the future of Asia and that of the world as well.
How to seize the opportunity and meet the challenges? How to
continue the efforts to promote the establishment of a just and
reasonable new international political and economic order of peace
and stability and work hard to bring into the 21st century a new
Asia and a new world with lasting peace and universal prosperity?
These are the pressing tasks to be tackled by the statesmen and
people from Asia, including China and Thailand, and the rest of
the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0465 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuala Lumpur Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange closed higher Friday with strong bargain
hunting on highly capitalized stocks.
</P>
<P>
At the close, the 100-quality stocks Composite Index firmed 9.8
points to 745.32, the all-share Emas Index rose 2.95 points to
193.26, the Industrial Index gained 17.27 points to 1,329.11 and
the Second Board Index added 1.8 points to 162.07.
</P>
<P>
Gainers whipped losers by 541 to 116 while 86 counters were
unchanged, 177 untraded and 12 suspended.
</P>
<P>
The day's turnover, however, narrowed to 259.226 million shares
worth 508.35 million ringgit (133.776 million U.S. dollars) from
333.89 million shares valued at 627.88 million ringgit (165.231
million dollars) on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0466 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of President Jiang Zemin's Speech in Thailand (Part Three) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At present, the international situation is undergoing profound
changes and, on the whole, it has been moving towards relaxation
since the end of the Cold War. There has been an increasingly
louder and bigger voice for peace, stability and development in
the world. However, the world is far from being tranquil.
Hegemonism and power politics still exist and have even developed
in the international political, economic and security fields. The
new "Gunboat Policy" and the economic neo-colonialism pursued by
some big powers have severely undermined the sovereign
independence and the development interests of many small- and
medium-sized countries, and have threatened world peace and
international security. To maintain world peace and promote
common development, all the countries must strictly abide by the
basic norms governing international relations that have been
established since the end of the war against Fascism in the world,
including the Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence and the
purposes and principles of the UN Charter. No country should be
allowed to defy the laws, or willfully violate and trample on
these norms. All the countries, regardless of their strength, are
equal members of the international community. Internal affairs of
any country should be decided by its own people, while
international affairs should be settled by all through discussion.
This is the common will of all the peace-loving countries and
peoples, and it is also an irresistible historical trend.
</P>
<P>
International economic exchanges should be conducted in
compliance with the principles of equality, mutual benefit and
common development. In working out new rules for international
economic and trade activities, the reasonable demands of the
developing countries should be adequately reflected and their
legitimate rights and interests be protected. The developed
countries should shoulder more obligations and they have the
capability to do so. No country should be allowed to make use of
its advantages to seek privileges and impair other countries'
interests in the process of economic globalisation Economic
cooperation and foreign aid with political strings attached are
never welcome. Trade protectionism of various forms undermines
not only the interests of others, but also those of the practicing
states in the end. Historical lessons in this regard should not
be forgotten. The malignant trend of the continuously widening
gap between the South and the North deserves our high attention
and concrete and effective measures should be taken to gradually
settle the problem. Otherwise, the poor will become poorer and
the rich richer. In that case, not only will developing countries
find their economic development hampered, but developed countries
will also find it difficult to achieve a steady economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0467 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of President Jiang Zemin's Speech in Thailand (Part Four) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To safeguard international security, the Cold War mentality
must be completely cast away. A lasting peace of the international
community must be built on the basis of a new security concept
through enhanced mutual confidence and common interests. Mutual
confidence should be enhanced through dialogue, security should be
sought through cooperation, and disputes settled through peaceful
means on the basis of mutual respect for state sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Both China and ASEAN countries are advocators for a new
international order. We are all developing countries and neighbors
linked by mountains and waters. Our consensus on strategic issues
is increasing. Both China and ASEAN countries need to maintain
good-neighborliness and friendship with each other. So long as we
always try to resort to friendly consultation, there is no dispute
that cannot be solved. China and ASEAN countries should always be
good neighbors, good friends, and good partners. In the course of
the Asian financial crisis, China shared the difficulties of
Thailand and other ASEAN countries, went through thick and thin
together with them, and provided assistance within its capacity to
the affected countries. China is ready to have in-depth
discussions with the relevant ASEAN countries on the principles
and ways of safeguarding peace and stability in this region as
well as in the South China Sea. It stands for settlement of
existing differences through friendly consultation and negotiation.
China respects ASEAN's efforts for the establishment of a zone of
peace, freedom and neutrality. It respects and supports the
Protocol to the Treaty on Southeast Asia Nuclear Weapon Free Zone.
We welcome the economic integration of ASEAN and are taking an
active part in the cooperation in the Lancang-Mekong River basin
development. We attach great importance to the ASEAN Vision 2020
and the Hanoi Plan of Action, and hope to deepen cooperation with
ASEAN in the economic, trade, scientific and technological, social
and other fields. I have always believed that a united and
prosperous ASEAN is an important force for peace and development
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Recent years have witnessed an all-around and deepened
development of China-ASEAN relations. In the Joint Statement
issued by leaders of ASEAN countries and myself in 1997, it was
decided to build a partnership of good-neighbourliness and mutual
trust between China and ASEAN. That document has charted a course
and provided a framework for the future development of relations
between the two sides. China has signed or issued documents for
the 21st-century-oriented cooperation with Thailand, Vietnam,
Malaysia and Brunei respectively, and it hopes to further deepen
the mutually beneficial cooperation with all ASEAN countries.
China and ASEAN have become each other's important trade and
investment partners. We have the reason to believe that, so long
as the Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence are adhered to,
there is a bright prospect for the development of the friendly
relations between China and ASEAN.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0468 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of President Jiang Zemin's Speech in Thailand (Part Five) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ladies and Gentlemen,
</P>
<P>
The 20th century is one of earth-shaking changes for China.
Thanks to the pioneering work and arduous efforts by the People's
Republic of China over the past 50 years, especially over the last
20 years or so since the beginning of reform and opening-up, the
overall national strength and the living standards of the people
have been improved in no small ways. Now, the Chinese people are
advancing with big strides along the path of building socialism
with Chinese characteristics. It is our strategic objective to
basically realize modernization and build China into a prosperous
and strong socialist country with a high degree of democracy and
civilization by the middle of the 21st century. In the new century,
the Chinese people will stand ready to work together with the
people of Thailand, ASEAN, Asia and other countries in the world
for the lofty cause of peace and development in Asia and in the
world at large.
</P>
<P>
China's modernization drive calls for a long-term peaceful
international environment and a good surrounding environment. The
stability and development in China itself, peace and prosperity in
its surrounding areas and a new regional security order based on
the Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence are where the common
interests of Asian countries and also the fundamental interests of
China lie. China pursues an independent foreign policy of peace
and a defense policy of a defensive nature. A developed China will
pose no threat to any country, and it will only be conducive to
regional and world peace and prosperity. Even when China becomes
developed in future, it will continue to pursue unswervingly an
independent foreign policy of peace and will firmly stand together
with all other developing countries and all the peace-loving
countries and peoples. "Do unto others as you would have them do
unto you". China firmly opposes hegemonism and power politics and
will never seek hegemony -- that is a solemn commitment that the
Chinese Government and people have made to the whole world.
</P>
<P>
In the Chinese civilization of several thousand years, to keep
the nation unified has always been the main stream in China's
history and a lofty goal that the Chinese people have cherished
from generation to generation. There is but one China in the world
and Taiwan is an inalienable part of Chinese territory. To solve
the Taiwan question in accordance with the basic principles of "
peaceful reunification" and "one country, two systems" represents
the common aspiration of the entire Chinese people and the
overwhelming historical trend of China's development. The
situation in Hong Kong since its return to China has shown that
China's complete reunification is conducive to Asia's stability
and prosperity. The Chinese Government thinks highly of the
support given to it by the Thai Government and governments of
other ASEAN countries on the question of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Before I conclude, I also wish to say a few words to the young
people present here. The 21st century is yours. I am confident
that you will carry forward the fine tradition of your nation and
of other Asian nations, take up boldly the glorious mission of
developing your country and safeguarding regional and world peace
in your march to the new century, and work together with all
peoples of the world to build a better future for Asia and for the
world at large.
</P>
<P>
Thank you. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
