<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Irish Unionists Set Conditions on Peace Process Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's Ulster
Unionist Party (UUP) said on Friday it would take part initially
in a review of the British province's stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
But the pro-British party said full-scale participation in next
week's review, headed by former U.S. senator George Mitchell,
would depend on whether the republicans were truly committed to
peace.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released on Friday morning, the UUP ruled out
UUP leader David Trimble's face-to-face meeting with Sinn Fein
President Gerry Adams until he has proof that the republicans are
exclusively committed to peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
The party will not totally boycott the review of the workings
of the Good Friday Agreement due to start on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The party demanded that Mitchell establish at the review
whether Sinn Fein, the IRA's political wing, and the political
allies of pro-British loyalist militias, are committed to the
province's peace drive.
</P>
<P>
"This is the essential pre-requisite for success and will
determine our subsequent engagement in the review," the UUP said
in the statement.
</P>
<P>
"Having already indicated to Senator Mitchell in July that we
support a review, the party will therefore take it a stage at a
time, monitoring progress closely and take such action as it deems
necessary," it added.
</P>
<P>
The statement is a rebuff to Sinn Fein, which is expected to
decide whether it will participate in the review at a meeting of
the party's ruling council in Dublin on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The UUP said it is still considering legal action to overturn
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam's statement that the IRA
cease-fire is intact.
</P>
<P>
Twelve senior UUP party officials, including Trimble, are due
to meet on Friday and the party's ruling executive of around 100
members meets on Saturday to finalize policy regarding the review.
</P>
<P>
The peace process has been stalled for more than a year as the
UUP and Sinn Fein argued about IRA disarmament and the formation
of a coalition government for the British province.
</P>
<P>
The Ulster Unionists refused to form a power-sharing executive
with Sinn Fein because the IRA rejection demands that arms
decommissioning should start before the devolved government was
set up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
