<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Controversy over Interest Tax Makes Chinese Feel More Like Tax Payers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A Beijing woman in her fifties
complained to a police officer that she was kicked like a football,
shuttling between a police station and a government personnel
department, but the answer to the request for a residential ID was
still "not enough documents."
</P>
<P>
"You guys are spending tax payers' money just to keep my legs
busy!" she was almost yelling.
</P>
<P>
This was one of a number of incidents Xinhua reporters
encountered after the national legislature adopted amendments to
the Personal Income Tax Law on August 30 to allow the government
to tax hundreds of million of depositors on their savings interest.
Such incidents used to be impossible.
</P>
<P>
Stories on this topic has been making the rounds of all the
media in China. To the surprise of policy-makers, the new taxation
will not only increase revenues to the state coffer, but has also
spurred the public to be more aware of their obligations as tax
payers.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the second day after the law was passed, a group of
Qigong practitioners in a park were engaged in a dispute with
security officers there over why they were not allowed to clap
their hands.
</P>
<P>
One of the practitioners said, "We are tax payers, but you are
not doing your job right."
</P>
<P>
Never having heard of such accusations before, the security
officers looked rather embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
Liu Longxiang, a taxation professor with the Beijing
University, said that a "tax-payer mentality" is growing stronger
in the mind of the Chinese public as the government has been
launching high-profile reforms to the existing taxation system and
propagating the knowledge of law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0475 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Inflation Declines by 0.93 Pct in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia suffered a 0.93
percent deflation or negative inflation in August, the country's
sixth month of deflation in a row, according to the Central Bureau
of Statistics (BPS).
</P>
<P>
The negative monthly inflation rate was primarily caused by a
stability in the prices of most basic food commodities, especially
rice, Chief of the BPS Sugito Suwito told reporters here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia posted a deflation of 0.18 percent in March, 0.68
percent in April, 0.28 percent in May, 0.34 percent in June and
1.05 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
The government earlier projected an inflation target of 17
percent for the current 1999-2000 fiscal year which ended in March
next year, but recently revised it to 10 percent following
positive development in the country's macroeconomic picture.
</P>
</TEXT>
