<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0482 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EALAF Foreign Ministers to Meet in 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The first foreign ministers'
meeting of the East Asia-Latin America Forum (EALAF) has been
scheduled to be held in the Chilean capital of Santiago in the
first quarter of 2001.
</P>
<P>
Bilahari Kansikan and Christian Barros, coordinators of the
meeting and respectively heads of the Singapore and Chilean
delegations, announced the schedule at a press conference at the
end of the two-day inaugural EALAF meeting of officials Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kansikan described the inaugural meeting as "productive" and
"encouraging," saying there were a great deal of commitments made
by all participants and they shared a common view on the value of
the forum.
</P>
<P>
Citing the meeting as a very strong forward step, Kansikan said
there was an agreement that there is a great deal of potentials in
the two regions and this forum will make valuable contribution to
tapping the potentials.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed that the forum should be multidimensional in which
we have political, cultural, social as well as economic
dimensions," he said. He stressed, "The general purpose is to
promote that multidimensional understanding and over the time it
will enable us to realize the potential of relations in our
regions."
</P>
<P>
Calling the meeting the start of a long process, Kansikan said
participating countries proposed a lot of projects including three
by Singapore concerning economic study, a journalist visit program
and a travel fair.
</P>
<P>
In reply to questions, Kansikan confirmed that the forum only
composes sovereign states, saying it is not the same as the APEC
which has a much broader basis.
</P>
<P>
Barros said he agreed to Kansikan's assessment of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that the next EALAF meeting of officials will
be held next August to prepare for the foreign ministers' meeting.
</P>
<P>
The EALAF was proposed by Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok
Tong during his October 1998 visit to Chile.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that strengthening dialogue and
cooperation between East Asia and Latin America conforms to the
fundamental interests of the people in the two regions and is
conducive to enhancing the role of developing countries in the
international affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
