<HEADLINE> Relations Between UNITA, Caprivi Separatists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Namibian authorities are
currently making an investigation on the possible relations
between Angolan rebels and Namibian secessionists, chief of
general staff of the Namibian army was quoted on Friday by Jornal
de Angola newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
General Martin Shalli affirmed that according to the
confessions of the seven captives, who were apprehended by the
Namibian government troops on August 2 during a battle against
armed separatists in the Caprivi Strip, in northeast Namibia, they
are "undoubtedly" members of the rebel UNITA.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian government is currently investigating if they did
that on their own account or according to instructions of Jonas
Savimbi, head of the rebellious National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA), said the general.
</P>
<P>
It was also reported that 14 people were killed during the
battle in the city of Katima Mulilo in the Caprivi Strip, which
has common frontiers with Angola, Zimbabwe, Zambia and Botswana.
Some separatists were reported to have fled into Angolan
territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
