<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0489 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Remains Challenge to Mankind: Chinese Law-Maker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- To seek lasting peace and
sustainable development in the world remains the challenge to
mankind on the threshold of the 21st century, a senior Chinese
official said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
On the threshold of the new century, mankind is confronted with
an urgent task of establishing a fair and equitable new
international and regional political and economic order, Zeng
Jianhui, head of the Chinese Delegation, told the Asian
Parliamentarians' Conference for Peace and Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Law-makers from 33 Asian countries are here to attend the
four-day conference which opened Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zeng noted that the new international order should, first of
all, serve to create a long-term stable and peaceful international
environment conducive to the development of all countries in the
world. It should also embody the universal aspiration and common
interests of the people of all countries and reflect the demand of
history and the progress of the time.
</P>
<P>
Zeng, who is also chairman of the Foreign Affairs Committee of
China' National People's Congress, pointed out that the core of
the principles of the U.N. Charter, the five Principles of
Peaceful Coexistence and the Ten principles of Bandung Conference
is mutual respect for sovereignty and territorial integrity,
non-aggression, non-interference in each other's internal affairs,
equality and mutual benefit and peaceful coexistence.
</P>
<P>
Without sovereignty, there would be no independence, security
and human rights to speak of, he said, adding, "The principle of
respect for sovereignty brooks no challenge, otherwise, there
would be no tranquillity for the international community and no
guarantee for the security of medium- and small-sized countries."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the allegation that human rights override
sovereignty is nothing but an excuse by hegemonism to interfere in
the internal affairs of other countries and constitutes a grave
threat to world peace.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the disputes between states, he said they should
only be resolved through peaceful negotiation without resorting to
threat or use of force.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that no country or group of countries has the
privilege to override the international community, nor does any
country has the right to impose its own values on others. "No
country should damage other countries' security under any
pretext."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese law-maker called for the establishment of a just
and rational new international economic order as early as
possible, saying developing countries must unite so as to break
the monopoly of world economic affairs by a small number of
developed countries.
</P>
<P>
"Developing countries should be allowed equal and full
participation in the current international financial reform,
international economic decision-making process and the formation
of new rules of the game," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zeng said China finds it necessary to enhance regional economic
cooperation and South-South cooperation, which has proved to be an
effective way to promote lasting prosperity at the national and
regional levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
