<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Dispute over Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators have overcome the last obstacle to an agreement on
the implementation of a U.S.-brokered peace agreement Friday,
Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted senior diplomatic sources in Jerusalem as
saying that the two sides had reached agreement on the release of
Palestinian prisoners jailed by Israel.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the Palestinians had accepted the Israeli
proposal that Israel releases 350 Palestinian political
prisoners. The Palestinians had demanded the release of 400
political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli sources said a signing ceremony would probably
take place Saturday night, after the end of the Jewish Sabbath, in
the Egyptian Red Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
But U.S. sources said there would be chances that the ceremony
be held Friday afternoon in Sharm el-Sheikh before the Jewish
Sabbath starts later in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Prime Minister's Office has not confirmed the
reports.
</P>
<P>
The settlement was achieved after visiting U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright intervened to mediate between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
A tentatively planned signing ceremony in the Egyptian port
city of Alexandria Thursday afternoon was scotched by continued
difference between Israel and the Palestinians over the prisoner
issue. Albright had planned to attend the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
She held talks with Palestinian National Authority Chairman
Yasser Arafat Thursday evening in Alexandria before flying to
Israel for an immediate meeting with Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Barak's office issued the statement after the meeting, which
lasted for three and a half hours, saying that the Israeli side
expected answers from the Palestinian side over the Israeli
proposal on the prisoners issue Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Palestinian negotiators stayed in Alexandria Friday
morning, apparently preparing for a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
Albright postponed a meeting with Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy scheduled at 1100 a.m. (0900 GMT). Israel Radio said
she would now focus on a possible signing ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
