<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Women Take Clean Sweep of Medals by sportswriter Cao Li </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- South Korean women took a
clean sweep of medals in the individual competition at the Asian
Archery Championships here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kang Hyun Ji, 22, defeated compatriot Kim Du Ri 112-107 points
in the final to become the Asian champion. Kim won the silver
medal.
</P>
<P>
In the match for the bronze medal, Lee Hee Jung beat China's
Zhang Lili 111-103. Local favorite He Ying finished a lowly fifth.
</P>
<P>
Kang, a college junior, also set two Asian records, scoring 172
points for the 18-arrow match in the second round and 115 points
for the 12-arrow match during the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
The old 18-arrow mark of 170 points was set by South Korea's
Yun Hye Young at the last championships in Langkawi, Malaysia in
November 1997 while the previous 12-arrow record of 114 points was
registered by Lee Mi Jeong, also from South Korea, at Bangkok,
Thailand in October last year.
</P>
<P>
"I did not expect I would win the gold," Kang told Xinhua. "I
only thought I might reach the final."
</P>
<P>
Kang, a Christian who began archery training 12 years ago,
added: "During the final I thought of nothing. I just kept praying.
"
</P>
<P>
The two-time world junior champion said her next target is to
get herself selected for the national team for next summer's
Olympic Games in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
"I will have to practice more and be mentally prepared for a
tough competition," she said of the South Korean national
championships in November, which is dubbed as a selection
competition for the national team in Sydney. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
