<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0504 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Declares September as Y2K Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada has declared the month of September 1999 as "Y2K
Consciousness Month," Presidential Spokesman Jerry Barican said
Friday in a new release.
</P>
<P>
Barican said the initiative is part of the government's
stepped-up campaign for public consciousness of the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Barican said, it is also aimed at allaying fears
of a meltdown of public services if computers fail to recognize
the date when their internal clock rolls into the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came as the Social Security System (SSS) and
the Government Service Insurance System (GSIS) announced that they
do not expect any interruption of their services due to the
millennium bug at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Various sectors have aired apprehension that the country may
not be ready to face the millennium bug and that public services
may be temporarily halted, should the government computers fail to
recognize the date when the new millennium comes.
</P>
<P>
In signing the proclamation, Barican said, "the president cited
the need to highlight the efforts being undertaken by both
government and the private sector performing critical missions
toward addressing the Y2K factor."
</P>
<P>
Y2K Commission Chairman Amable Aquiluz said earlier that the
GSIS and the SSS are very likely to complete preparations
relatively early, adding that the former is now 77 percent
complete while the latter is 80 percent complete.
</P>
<P>
According to a Y2K Commission report, the finance sector is 95
percent Y2K ready; utilities and manufacturing, 80 percent;
telecommunication and transportation, 79 percent; government
services, 77 percent; and health care, 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K problem is likely to affect computer systems that could
not properly read dates from January 1, 2000 onward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
