<HEADLINE> Eritrea Denies Attacking Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Eritrean government has
denied Ethiopia's accusation of mounting attacks at Chin Keren on
the Zalambessa front, according to a press release available here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The press release issued by the Eritrean Foreign Ministry
Thursday said, "the recent accusation falls into the pattern of
ridiculous allegations" that Ethiopia "has been leveling against
Eritrea" throughout the past week.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean foreign ministry claimed that the apparent purpose
of Ethiopia's accusations to divert international attention from
Ethiopia's reluctance to accept the OAU peace process.
</P>
<P>
It said that there has not been any fighting on any of the
fronts in the past two months since the start of the rains, "apart
from the occasional shelling invariably initiated by Ethiopia."
</P>
<P>
And it reiterated that Eritrea has accepted the OAU peace
process and expressed its readiness to implement all its
provisions in good faith and without delay.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the Office of the Ethiopian Government
Spokesperson said in a statement that Ethiopian troops on the same
day repelled an offensive by the Eritrean troops at Chin Keren on
the Zalambessa front.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean attack continued through Wednesday night and ended
Thursday morning at 6:00 a.m. local time, the statement alleged.
</P>
<P>
Zalambessa, a border town of Ethiopia, is situated in the mid
way of the 1,000 km-long Ethio-Eritrean war front. 
</P>
</TEXT>
