<HEADLINE>    ... Madeleine Albright. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Earlier, both Israeli and Palestinian sources said that
they had overcome the last obstacle to an agreement on the
implementation of the Wye agreement, the dispute over the
release of Palestinian prisoners jailed by Israel.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the Palestinians had accepted the Israeli
proposal that Israel release 350 Palestinian security prisoners,
or political prisoners called by the Palestinians. The
Palestinians have demanded the release of 400 political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here quoted Palestinian National Authority
Chairman Yasser Arafat, who is in the Egyptian port city of
Alexandria Friday, as saying that the two sides had reached
a deal and would hold a signing ceremony in the Egyptian Red
Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
The settlement was achieved after visiting U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright intervened to mediate between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
A tentatively planned signing ceremony in Alexandria Thursday
afternoon was scotched by continued difference between Israel
and the Palestinians over the prisoner issue. Albright had
planned to attend the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
She held talks with Palestinian National Authority Chairman
Yasser Arafat Thursday evening in Alexandria before flying to
Israel into an immediate meeting with Prime Minister Ehud Barak,
which Albright described as "excellent" at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
Barak's office issued a statement after the meeting which
lasted for three and a half hours, saying that the Israeli sides
expected answers from the Palestinian side over the Israeli
proposal on the prisoners issue Friday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
