<HEADLINE> Palestinians, Israelis Agree on Revised Wye </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
said on Friday that the Palestinians have reached an agreement
with the Israelis on a revised Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israelis have agreed on all points,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency (MENA) quoted Arafat as saying.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was interviewed at the Alexandria airport before
boarding a flight to return to Gaza.
</P>
<P>
He said the agreement on the implementation of the Wye accord
signed last October would be signed in the Egyptian Red Sea resort
of Sharm el Sheikh on Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
Reports on earlier Friday said the Palestinians and Israelis
still differ on one issue: a clause in the emerging accord barring
both sides from taking unilateral actions in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
In their talks on Friday, the two sides settled what had been
the salient point of disagreement during the past few days: the
number of Palestinians to be released from Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
Two senior Israeli officials have reportedly said on condition
on anonymity that the issue was resolved when the Palestinians
agreed to the release of 350 Palestinians held for anti-Israeli
activities instead of 400 they initially insisted on. 
</P>
