</P>
<P>
-- U.S. State Secretary Madeleine K. Albright and her top
Middle East Peace negotiators sought early Friday to restart
stalled negotiations on a long-delayed Israeli troop withdrawal
from the West Bank that is seen as critical to restoring trust
between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
-- Violence mounted in East Timor Thursday as pro-Indonesian
militias opposed to independence for the territory continued their
rampage, killing three more United Nations workers, threatening
journalists and creating a climate of fear that caused both
Timorese and foreign visitors to flee.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- After weeks of negotiations, NATO and United Nations
officials have agreed to allow a part of the Kosovo Liberation
Army, the guerrilla force of Kosovo Albanians, to survive as a
lightly armed civilian emergency force.
</P>
<P>
-- On her first trip to the Middle East since Ehud Barak came
to power as the Israeli Prime Minister, Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright has hit a snag, with the Israelis and the
Palestinians failing to deliver an agreement for a signing
ceremony in Egypt that she had hoped to preside over.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- After years of stagnant wages, U.S. organized labor is
aggressively seeking big pay gains, raising the prospect that
tight labor markets may finally be leading to wage inflation.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. productivity growth slowed in the second quarter to 0.6
percent, revised down from the earlier estimate of 1.3 percent.But
many economists view the falloff as temporary. 
</P>
