<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, Palestinians Close to Deal on Implementing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy said Friday that Israel and the Palestinians were very
close to an agreement on the implementation of a U.S.-brokered
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
"We are very close to concluding an agreement on the Wye River
Accord," Levy said at a joint news conference after talks with
visiting United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
"It is never in doubt that Israel will implement the Wye
agreement...I hope the other sides will accept its responsibility
in the process," he said, referring to the interim agreement
signed and then frozen by former hard-line Israeli prime minister
Benjamin Netanyahu last year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, both Israeli and Palestinian sources said they had
overcome the last major obstacle to an agreement on the
implementation of the Wye agreement: the dispute over the release
of Palestinian prisoners jailed by Israel.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the Palestinians had accepted the Israeli
proposal that Israel release 350 Palestinian security prisoners,
or political prisoners called by the Palestinians. The
Palestinians had demanded the release of 400 political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports from Egypt quoted Palestinian National
Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat as saying that a deal had
already been reached and a signing ceremony would be held in the
Egyptian Red Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
But after arriving in Gaza from the Egyptian port city of
Alexandria, Arafat told reporters that a deal had yet to be
finalized and there were still difficult issues.
</P>
<P>
A tentatively planned signing ceremony in Alexandria Thursday
afternoon was scotched by continued difference between Israel and
the Palestinians over the prisoner issue.
</P>
<P>
The dispute forced Albright, who had planned to oversee the
ceremony, to intervene to mediate between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
She held talks with Arafat and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Thursday evening in Alexandria before flying to Israel into an
immediate meeting with Prime Minister Ehud Barak, which Albright
described as "excellent" at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
Barak's office issued the statement after the meeting, which
lasted for three and a half hours, saying that the Israeli side
expected answers from the Palestinian side over the Israeli
proposal on the prisoners issue Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the two sides were trying to resolve a last
dispute on the draft deal, the one banning the two sides from
taking unilateral actions in Gaza and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
These actions include the building of Jewish settlements by
the Israeli side and a unilateral declaration of Palestinian
state by the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said this issue might be resolved by a letter
written by the U.S. and attached to the agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
