<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0537 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Begin Technological Research in Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- More than 20 scientists have
arrived in Shenzhen, one of China's five special economic zones,
to begin a research project involving photoelectron technology at
Shenzhen University in south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Headed by Niu Hanben, 59, an academician of the Chinese Academy
of Sciences (CAS), the scientists, who moved into Shenzhen on
Thursday, will establish a photoelectron research institute for
the university. Niu is Shenzhen's first CAS academician.
</P>
<P>
At an average age of 41, the scientists are famous in the
fields of photoelectron, laser, exactitude machinery,
semiconductor, and image treatment.
</P>
<P>
The university has provided apartments and vehicles for the
scientists. Additionally, the city government of Shenzhen will
build a 5,000-square-meter laboratory for the researchers.
</P>
<P>
The scientists will conduct a series of high-tech experiments
on digital hanging-style television, new semiconductor material
and semiconductor lighting technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
