</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0538 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin on International Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A lasting peace of the
international community must be built on the basis of a new
security concept through enhanced mutual confidence and common
interests, Chinese President Jiang Zemin said in Bangkok today.
</P>
<P>
"To safeguard the international security, the Cold War
mentality must be cast away completely. Mutual confidence should
be enhanced through dialogue, security should be sought through
cooperation, and disputes settled through peaceful means on the
basis of mutual respect for state sovereignty," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who arrived here Thursday afternoon on a state visit,
said this during a speech entitled "Enhance Good-Neighborliness
and Friendship and Build a Better Future Together" at the National
Cultural Center of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
He spoke at the invitation of the International Studies Center
of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
At present, the international situation is undergoing profound
changes and, on the whole, it has been moving towards relaxation
since the end of the Cold War, Jiang said, adding there has been
an increasingly louder and bigger voice for peace, stability and
development in the world.
</P>
<P>
However, he went on to say, "The world is far from being
tranquil. Hegemonism and power politics still exist and have even
been developed in the international political, economic and
security fields.
</P>
<P>
The new "gunboat policy" and the economic neo-colonialism
pursued by some big powers have severely undermined the sovereign
independence and the development interests of many small- and
medium-sized countries, and have threatened world peace and
international security, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
To maintain world peace and promote common development, he
stressed, all countries must strictly abide by the basic norms
governing international relations that have been established since
the end of the war against Fascism in the world, including the
Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence and the purposes and
principles of the UN Charter.
</P>
<P>
No country should be allowed to defy the laws, or willfully
violate and trample on these norms, Jiang said, adding that all
countries, regardless of their strength, are equal members of the
international community.
</P>
<P>
The internal affairs of any country should be decided by its
own people, while international affairs should be addressed by all
through discussion, he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted this is the common will of all the peace-loving
countries and peoples, and it is also an irresistible historical
trend.
</P>
<P>
On international economic exchanges, Jiang said this should be
conducted in compliance with the principles of equality, mutual
benefit and common development.
</P>
<P>
In working out new rules for international economic and trade
activities, Jiang said, the reasonable demands of the developing
countries should be adequately reflected and their legitimate
rights and interests be protected. He also urged the developed
countries to shoulder more obligations as they have the capability
to do so.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the malignant trend of the continuously widening
gap between the South and the North should deserve high attention
and concrete and effective measures be taken to gradually settle
the problem.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, Jiang noted, the poor will become poorer and the
rich richer.
</P>
<P>
In that case, not only will developing countries find their
economic development hampered, but developed countries will also
find it difficult to achieve a steady economic growth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0539 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Build More Houses for Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
targeted to provide 781,213 homes households for 1999-2004,
Housing and Urban Development Council (HUDCC) Secretary Karina
David said Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a report to Congress, David said of this total about 509,303
households or 65 percent correspond to the socialized sector, that
is, the informal settler, income poor or homeless.
</P>
<P>
He said the HUDCC will mobilize approximately 200.5 billion
pesos (5 billion U.S. dollars) in public and private funds to
provide decent and affordable housing to those families, which is
the bottom 30 percent of Philippine economic society.
</P>
<P>
For the year 2000, the government is targeting to provide
social and economic housing to 144,738 homes or 18.5 percent of
the overall six-year planned target, with an estimated funding
requirement of 31.7 billion pesos (792.5 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The HUDCC said during the past year, the government housing
agencies provided socialized and low-cost housing to 89,516
households valued at 14.9 billion pesos (372.5 million dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
