<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Encourage Entry of More Foreign Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
continue with its policy of liberalizing the banking environment
and allowing the entry of more foreign banks, Presidential
Spokesman Jerry Barican said Friday in a news release.
</P>
<P>
Barican said this policy does not pose a threat to the local
banking industry but will further strengthen it since local banks
would be able to develop their expertise and resources to meet the
growing needs of their clientele.
</P>
<P>
Smaller banks, on the other hand, will also be able to find
their "niche" in the banking system by undertaking specialized
services that larger banks are unable to offer, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Barican stressed that "some macroeconomic mechanisms
would have to be put in place to ensure that majority of the
assets of the banking industry will remain within the hands of
Filipinos."
</P>
<P>
He said the Central Bank of the Philippines will continue to
encourage the consolidations and mergers among local banks by
extending short-term incentives to those planning to combine their
resources, services and technological know-how.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's move to encourage the mergers of local banks
is part of the measures being implemented to further strengthen
the local banking industry, which has remained stable despite the
economic crisis that had swept across Asia.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada has vowed to institute
reforms in the banking industry to make the economy more
competitive and has urged the congress to pass his
administration's priority measure which seeks amendments to the
General Banking Act. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0547 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana President Defends State of Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Botswana President Festus
Mogae Friday defended Thursday's declaration of a state of
emergency ahead of the country's general elections scheduled for
October 16, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Mogae declared the emergency in order to recall parliament and
amend the Electoral Act to allow 60,000 more voters to take part
in the elections.
</P>
<P>
The 60,000 voters registered during a supplementary
registration exercise, but were not included in the voters' roll.
</P>
<P>
According to Section 27 of the Electoral Act, however, the
supervisor of elections is barred from preparing, publishing or
certifying a roll of voters after the president has issued an
election writ.
</P>
<P>
Mogae issued the writ for election date last week.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the presidential office said that Mogae learnt
only Monday that the country's Independent Electoral Commission
(IEC) had been unable to finish its work to enable the 60,000
names to be added to the voters' rolls.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to criticisms that the state of emergency was too
dramatic a way of dealing with the problem, Mogae's spokesman
Andrew Sesinyi said the president had no other legal options.
</P>
<P>
"He could not consider any criticism his action might attract.
The only issue was that 60,000 people would have been denied their
constitutional right to vote, had he not done what he did. That
was unacceptable to him," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sesinyi said the matter was not a crisis as no freedom or
rights had been suspended. The problem was being rectified in a
prompt and lawful way.
</P>
<P>
Mogae had been under the impression the IEC would continue
working until October 10. Neither he, the chairman of the IEC, nor
the attorney-general had realized that once a writ of election had
been issued, the IEC could not make any further changes to the
rolls.
</P>
<P>
"The president had been told the IEC would have completed its
work by October 10, in time for elections in October as has been
the case for the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
"Parliament was dissolved, the only way it could be reconvened
was through a state of emergency," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
When the house reconvenes Monday ostensibly to debate the state
of emergency, the more important matter on the order paper will be
amendments to the Electoral Act to allow the IEC to carry on its
work despite the writ of election.
</P>
<P>
Mogae has also canceled next week's trip to a special meeting
of the Organization of African Unity in Libya.
</P>
<P>
Sesinyi refused to suggest who had been responsible for the
debacle. He said the matter would be investigated.
</P>
<P>
"We are taking stock and asking questions. The emergency will
be lifted as soon as all the necessary things have been done,
after the IEC has completed its task and parliament met and
amended the law as necessary," he said.
</P>
<P>
Botswana has a population of 1.5 million, of which 900,000 are
eligible for the voting. Including the 60,000 disqualified voters,
460,000, or 51 percent of the eligible voters, have registered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
