<HEADLINE> Chinese President Calls for Judicial Cooperation with Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese President
Jiang Zemin Friday called on the judicial departments of China and
Thailand to further expand bilateral exchanges and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with the Thai Supreme Court President Pintip
Sucharitkul here, Jiang hoped that bilateral judicial cooperation
should be particularly conducted to combat transnational organized
crimes related to drug trafficking, smuggling, economic crimes and
illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said China's great achievements in economic construction
since its opening-up and reform 20 years ago could not be
separated from its efforts to build and perfect the legal system.
</P>
<P>
Rule of law constitutes a fundamental policy of the Chinese
government, which also stems from the need to develop the
socialist market economy and provides an important guarantee for
maintaining the long-term and sustained stability of the country,
said the Chinese president.
</P>
<P>
Hence, Jiang said, the Chinese government highly values
judicial reform while strengthening legislation.
</P>
<P>
He said that China and Thailand now enjoy close ties of
cooperation, which he believes could not be secured without the
efforts made by people from all walks of life. The Supreme Court
of Thailand, in particular, has played an important role in the
development of such ties, he said.
</P>
<P>
Pintip said the Sino-Thai judicial cooperation has been
proceeding well. Both sides have signed a treaty on judicial
assistance. The two countries have cooperated well in combating
drug trafficking, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped for closer exchanges and cooperation between
China and Thailand in the judicial sphere in the future.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Jiang also met with Thai Privy
Councilor Prem Tinsulanonda. The Chinese president believed that
Prem, also former Thai prime minister and an old friend of the
Chinese people, will continue to make new contributions to the
development of the full-fledged Sino-Thai friendship and
cooperation in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Prem noted that as an old friend of China, he keenly hopes that
the friendly relations between Thailand and China will continue to
grow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
