<DOCNO> XIE19990903.0555 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Calls for Good Drug Donation Practice in New Guidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (
WHO) has issued new guidelines for drug donations during
emergencies since the disposal of unwanted drugs has made a bad
situation worse in some cases, according to a WHO press release
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"As soon as any disaster reaches our television screens, many
drugs, the great majority sent with the best of intentions, are
dispatched to the scene of the emergency," said Dr Jonathan Quick,
Director of WHO's Department of Essential Drugs and Other
Medicines.
</P>
<P>
"However, there have also been problems with some drug
donations," he added. "They fail to meet the most urgent real
health needs and, once in the recipient country, they clog up
already overloaded distribution systems and become difficult to
dispose of," said Quick.
</P>
<P>
A recent WHO survey of 108 drug donation lists submitted to the
Albanian Ministry of Health during May 1999 found that half of
these lists only mentioned trade names, many of which were unknown
to local health professionals; only 56 percent included
information on shelf-life, of which about 41 percent of the drugs
had a remaining shelf-life of less than one year; and 18 percent
of donations contained small packs of free samples or drugs
returned to pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
In its new guidelines, WHO stressed that none of the above-
mentioned practices are acceptable.
</P>
<P>
It repeated its plea to donors to ensure that their donations
are of maximum benefit to the recipient; respect the wishes and
authority of the recipient; strictly avoid any double standards in
quality; and are based on effective communication between donor
and recipient.
</P>
<P>
WHO said that the release of the revised guidelines is
particularly timely in light of the flux of drug donations into
Turkey following the earthquake there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
