<HEADLINE> Xinhua Photo List For September 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Following is a list of the
photo items released by Xinhua today:
1. An employee with a popular fast-food restaurant delivers
Youtiao, a typical Chinese diet for breakfast, to Madame Lin at
her home in Shanghai. Lin made the order via the Internet just 20
minutes ago. Estimates say one in every ten households in Shanghai
owns a computer.
2. Visitors tour the newly-opened Palace Museum of Duke Bo in
Tongliao, the duke's hometown in Inner Mongolia.
3. A huge moon cake is displayed at a supermarket to attract
customers in Beijing. Although the traditional Mid-autumn Festival
is more than 20 days away, eager vendors are already busy selling
moon cakes. The Chinese have a tradition of taking moon cakes for
the festival.
4. The picture shows a newly-installed radio telescope in the dusk
of an evening at a mountainous scenic spot in Urumqi, Xinjiang
Autonomous Region.
5. A painter paints the gate of a traditional Chinese house in the
style of Qing and Ming dynasties in Beijing. All the houses on the
south side of west Chang'an Avenue have taken on a new look after
two months of renovation and decoration on the eve of the 50th
anniversary of the founding of New China.
6. He Yiqiu talks to his friend with a mobile phone before his
participation in China's first online survival test. He is to be
locked alone in a room for 72 hours. The only way to obtain food
and water and to contact with others is a computer. Together with
him, 11 other volunteers took part in the trial in Beijing,
Shanghai and Guangzhou.
7. An employee operates a new system at the newly-built cargo-
processing building of the Capital International Airport in
Beijing. It leads other Chinese airports in terms of freight
handling capacity.
8. Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao meets with Uruguayan Defense
Minister Juan Luis Storace.
9. Premier Zhu Rongji meets with Eamonn Barnes, president of the
International Association of Prosecutors (IAP).
10. Premier Zhu Rongji meets with chairman of the Korean Chamber
of Commerce and Industry Kim Sang-Ha.
</P>
