<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unemployment Drops Back to 29-Year Low in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. unemployment rate
dropped back to a 29-year low of 4.2 percent in August because of
gains in computer services and health care jobs, the Labor
Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Department reported that the decrease in August's
unemployment rate followed a 4.3 percent rate in July. Despite the
decline in the unemployment rate, employers added a
smaller-than-expected 124,000 jobs to their payrolls in August,
following a gain of 338,000 jobs in July.
</P>
<P>
In August, average hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation
pressures, grew a tiny 0.2 percent to 13.30 dollars, a 3.5 percent
increase compared to a year ago. That was the third straight
monthly rise, but slightly slower than 0.3 percent increase in
July.
</P>
<P>
The report showed the number of service sector jobs increased
by 132,000 last month, led by gains in computer services which
grew by 15,000 jobs. Doctors offices, hospitals and other
health-care facilities added 19,000 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers, still feeling the lingering affects of the
global financial crisis, cut 63,000 jobs in August. That more than
wiped out an increase of 51,000 jobs in July.
</P>
<P>
The loss in manufacturing jobs hit the apparel and industrial
machinery industries hardest, while car and furniture makers
continued to add jobs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, construction jobs declined by 29,000, largely
offsetting gains in the previous two months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
