<HEADLINE> Afghan Opposition Sets up Leadership Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's opposition
alliance Friday set up a leadership council with ousted president
Burhanuddin Rabbani as its chairman, Afghan sources in the
northeastern Pakistani city of Peshawar said.
</P>
<P>
The decision to set up the leadership council was made at a
meeting between Rabbani, former defense minister and opposition
commander Ahmed Shah Masood as well as Rabbani's close aid Abdur
Rab Rasool Sayyaf in Gulbahar, capital of Afghanistan's northern
Parwan province.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of former Afghan prime minister Gulbuddin
Hekmatyar, Shiite Hizb-e-Wehdat and Harakat-e-Islami factions also
attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the anti-Taliban leadership council also
included Maulvi Golam Mohammad, an Islamic scholar from Kandahar,
the stronghold of the Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance leaders also nominated ministers for a
10-member cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban alliance vowed that communists would not be
included in the cabinet and minorities would be given proper
representation in their government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
